Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.21,0:00:25.80,Default,,0,0,0,,There is an ongoing need\Nfor volunteers at Bethel
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.80,0:00:29.51,Default,,0,0,0,,and on theocratic construction projects.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.51,0:00:32.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Although the COVID-19 pandemic has limited
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.93,0:00:36.52,Default,,0,0,0,,the number of those who may be invited\Nat this time,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.52,0:00:40.11,Default,,0,0,0,,there is still a need for volunteers.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.10,0:00:42.48,Default,,0,0,0,,As you watch the following video,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.48,0:00:45.03,Default,,0,0,0,,please note the spirit displayed
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.02,0:00:49.02,Default,,0,0,0,,by those who make themselves available\Nfor Bethel service.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.32,0:00:55.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Making yourself available for Bethel service
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.20,0:00:57.41,Default,,0,0,0,,is like knocking on a door that leads
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.41,0:01:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,to many other privileges of service.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.00,0:01:02.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, to serve at Bethel
Dialogue: 0,0:01:02.17,0:01:05.09,Default,,0,0,0,,requires a self-sacrificing spirit
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.09,0:01:08.30,Default,,0,0,0,,and a willingness to serve\Nwherever there is a need,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.30,0:01:11.64,Default,,0,0,0,,in harmony with the attitude \Ndisplayed by the prophet Isaiah
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.63,0:01:13.72,Default,,0,0,0,,at Isaiah 6:8:
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.85,0:01:17.65,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then I heard the voice of Jehovah saying:
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.64,0:01:21.48,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Whom shall I send, and who will go for us?’
Dialogue: 0,0:01:21.48,0:01:25.19,Default,,0,0,0,,And I said: ‘Here I am! Send me!’”
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.36,0:01:29.24,Default,,0,0,0,,When Isaiah learned about an opportunity
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.23,0:01:33.07,Default,,0,0,0,,to do more in Jehovah’s service,\Nhe responded eagerly,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.07,0:01:37.78,Default,,0,0,0,,even though he did not know exactly\Nwhat he was going to be assigned to do.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.79,0:01:41.50,Default,,0,0,0,,It was enough for him to know\Nthat Jehovah was extending an invitation
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.50,0:01:43.88,Default,,0,0,0,,to serve in a special way,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.87,0:01:46.87,Default,,0,0,0,,and Isaiah wanted to volunteer.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:46.88,0:01:51.55,Default,,0,0,0,,The same spirit is shown\Nby Bethel family members worldwide.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.43,0:01:57.64,Default,,0,0,0,,If the Branch Committee determines\Nthat there is a need for your services,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.64,0:02:00.77,Default,,0,0,0,,they will decide where you can best be used,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.77,0:02:04.94,Default,,0,0,0,,whether at Bethel or perhaps\Non a theocratic construction assignment.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.81,0:02:09.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Submitting your application\Nmay open a door of opportunity
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.27,0:02:13.32,Default,,0,0,0,,to serve Jehovah and his organization\Nin a variety of ways.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.20,0:02:19.49,Default,,0,0,0,,That was an excerpt from the video
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.49,0:02:23.70,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}Making Yourself Available for Bethel Service.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.71,0:02:26.50,Default,,0,0,0,,If you are interested in serving at Bethel
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.50,0:02:29.42,Default,,0,0,0,,or on theocratic construction projects
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.42,0:02:32.26,Default,,0,0,0,,on a part-time or full-time basis,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.26,0:02:37.22,Default,,0,0,0,,please watch the entire video on jw.org.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.22,0:02:41.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Baptized Christians who are\N19 years of age or older
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.64,0:02:45.69,Default,,0,0,0,,and are interested in volunteering\Nshould apply.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.69,0:02:50.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Speak to your congregation secretary\Nfor more information.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.19,0:02:54.53,Default,,0,0,0,,If possible, please submit\Nyour application electronically
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.53,0:02:56.62,Default,,0,0,0,,on jw.org.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.41,0:03:03.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you ever found yourself in a situation\Nwhere your peace was threatened?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.41,0:03:05.62,Default,,0,0,0,,How did you handle it?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.62,0:03:09.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We can learn much\Nfrom the faithful man Jacob
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.29,0:03:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,about how to make peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.00,0:03:16.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Please open your Bibles\Nto Genesis chapter 26,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:16.38,0:03:21.09,Default,,0,0,0,,and follow along as Brother Mark Sanderson,\Na member of the Governing Body,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.10,0:03:23.27,Default,,0,0,0,,applies the lessons
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.27,0:03:26.44,Default,,0,0,0,,in the dramatic Bible reading\Nwith the theme
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.44,0:03:29.90,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}“{\r}Jacob—A Man Who Loved Peace.{\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}”
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.45,0:03:43.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you ever been\Nthe victim of oppression or injustice?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.33,0:03:45.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you been angered by something
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.33,0:03:47.67,Default,,0,0,0,,someone has said or done?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.66,0:03:49.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Who of us hasn’t?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.71,0:03:51.88,Default,,0,0,0,,In situations like that,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.88,0:03:53.92,Default,,0,0,0,,people who don’t know Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.92,0:03:57.88,Default,,0,0,0,,often react in a way\Nthat’s far from peaceful.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.88,0:04:00.88,Default,,0,0,0,,They retaliate; they fight;
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.89,0:04:03.23,Default,,0,0,0,,they hit back.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.22,0:04:06.97,Default,,0,0,0,,But we know that Jehovah\Nsees what happened,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:06.98,0:04:09.86,Default,,0,0,0,,and he can set matters straight.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.85,0:04:13.44,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re wise to remember the words of Jesus:
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.44,0:04:16.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“Happy are the mild-tempered.”
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.57,0:04:20.28,Default,,0,0,0,,“Happy are the peacemakers.”
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.28,0:04:24.66,Default,,0,0,0,,The Bible describes a man\Nwho remained mild and peaceable
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.66,0:04:29.29,Default,,0,0,0,,in some extremely difficult\Nand stressful situations.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.29,0:04:33.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Repeatedly, he chose not to fight,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.34,0:04:37.09,Default,,0,0,0,,preferring a course that led to peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.09,0:04:40.64,Default,,0,0,0,,That man was Jacob.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.63,0:04:43.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob learned from the peaceful example
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.97,0:04:46.76,Default,,0,0,0,,of his father, Isaac.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.77,0:04:49.23,Default,,0,0,0,,There was a famine in the land,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.23,0:04:52.53,Default,,0,0,0,,and Isaac moved his family to Gerar,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.52,0:04:57.28,Default,,0,0,0,,which was ruled by Abimelech,\Nking of the Philistines.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.28,0:05:00.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s read about the problems that arose
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.15,0:05:02.90,Default,,0,0,0,,and see how Isaac dealt with them.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.91,0:05:07.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Please turn to Genesis 26:12.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.71,0:05:13.42,Default,,0,0,0,,“And Isaac began to sow seed in that land,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.42,0:05:18.09,Default,,0,0,0,,“and in that year he reaped\N100 times what he sowed,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.09,0:05:21.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“for Jehovah was blessing him.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.51,0:05:23.68,Default,,0,0,0,,“The man became wealthy,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.68,0:05:28.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“and he continued to prosper\Nuntil he became very wealthy.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.68,0:05:32.77,Default,,0,0,0,,“He acquired flocks of sheep\Nand herds of cattle
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.77,0:05:35.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“and a large body of servants,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.52,0:05:39.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“and the Philistines began to envy him.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.53,0:05:42.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“So the Philistines took soil
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.20,0:05:46.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“and stopped up all the wells\Nthat his father’s servants had dug
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.20,0:05:48.83,Default,,0,0,0,,“in the days of Abraham.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.83,0:05:51.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“Abimelech then said to Isaac:
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.75,0:05:56.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Move from our neighborhood,\Nfor you have grown far stronger than we are.’
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.59,0:06:01.60,Default,,0,0,0,,“So Isaac moved from there\Nand encamped in the valley of Gerar
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.59,0:06:04.47,Default,,0,0,0,,“and began dwelling there.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.47,0:06:06.93,Default,,0,0,0,,“And Isaac again dug the wells
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.93,0:06:10.60,Default,,0,0,0,,“that had been dug\Nin the days of his father Abraham
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.60,0:06:15.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“but that the Philistines had stopped up\Nafter Abraham’s death,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.44,0:06:20.28,Default,,0,0,0,,“and he called them by the names\Nthat his father had given them.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.28,0:06:24.03,Default,,0,0,0,,“When the servants of Isaac\Nwere digging in the valley,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.03,0:06:26.87,Default,,0,0,0,,“they found a well of fresh water.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.87,0:06:29.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“And the shepherds of Gerar
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.99,0:06:33.95,Default,,0,0,0,,“began quarreling\Nwith the shepherds of Isaac, saying:
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.96,0:06:35.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘The water is ours!’
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.96,0:06:38.71,Default,,0,0,0,,“So he named the well Esek,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.71,0:06:41.80,Default,,0,0,0,,“because they had quarreled with him.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.80,0:06:44.68,Default,,0,0,0,,“And they started digging another well,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.68,0:06:47.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“and they began quarreling over it also.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.64,0:06:50.35,Default,,0,0,0,,“So he named it Sitnah.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.35,0:06:54.31,Default,,0,0,0,,“Later he moved away from there\Nand dug another well,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.31,0:06:57.31,Default,,0,0,0,,“but they did not quarrel over it.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.31,0:07:01.15,Default,,0,0,0,,“So he named it Rehoboth and said:
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.15,0:07:05.28,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘It is because now Jehovah\Nhas given us ample room
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.28,0:07:08.24,Default,,0,0,0,,“and has made us fruitful in the land.’
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.24,0:07:11.95,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then he went up from there to Beersheba.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.95,0:07:16.08,Default,,0,0,0,,“That night Jehovah appeared to him and said:
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.08,0:07:19.38,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I am the God of your father Abraham.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.38,0:07:23.05,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Do not be afraid, for I am with you,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.05,0:07:26.93,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and I will bless you\Nand multiply your offspring
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.93,0:07:29.56,Default,,0,0,0,,on account of Abraham my servant.’”
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.05,0:07:34.26,Default,,0,0,0,,The Philistines, motivated by envy,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.27,0:07:38.23,Default,,0,0,0,,stop up all the wells that Abraham had dug,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.23,0:07:42.15,Default,,0,0,0,,and the king asks Isaac\Nto move from the neighborhood.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.36,0:07:46.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Isaac now has a decision to make.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.32,0:07:49.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Perhaps some encourage him to stay put.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.57,0:07:52.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Think about how they might have reasoned:
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.74,0:07:55.53,Default,,0,0,0,,‘You’ve done nothing wrong, Isaac.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.54,0:07:58.75,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Jehovah told you that you and your offspring
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.75,0:08:00.79,Default,,0,0,0,,‘would possess the land.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.79,0:08:03.38,Default,,0,0,0,,‘You have nothing to fear.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.38,0:08:05.59,Default,,0,0,0,,‘You have many servants,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.59,0:08:08.55,Default,,0,0,0,,‘and they’re stronger than the Philistines.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.55,0:08:10.89,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Why not hit back
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.89,0:08:14.69,Default,,0,0,0,,against those who have done this\Nto your wells?’
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.68,0:08:18.39,Default,,0,0,0,,In this situation, what would you have done?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.64,0:08:22.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Isaac chooses a peaceful course.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.98,0:08:25.86,Default,,0,0,0,,He decides to move on.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:26.57,0:08:29.62,Default,,0,0,0,,This is not easy.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.61,0:08:32.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Isaac has many servants
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.03,0:08:36.12,Default,,0,0,0,,and flocks of sheep and herds of cattle.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.12,0:08:39.83,Default,,0,0,0,,He has tilled the ground and planted seed,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.83,0:08:42.79,Default,,0,0,0,,and it’s produced plentifully,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.79,0:08:47.63,Default,,0,0,0,,but he leaves that behind and moves on.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.63,0:08:52.18,Default,,0,0,0,,But Isaac’s troubles are not over.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.01,0:08:56.39,Default,,0,0,0,,In his new location, his servants dig wells
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.39,0:08:58.89,Default,,0,0,0,,and find fresh water.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.89,0:09:01.56,Default,,0,0,0,,But the shepherds in that area say:
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.56,0:09:04.48,Default,,0,0,0,,“The water is ours!”
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.48,0:09:07.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Isaac then digs another well,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:07.03,0:09:11.37,Default,,0,0,0,,but the local shepherds\Nquarrel about that one too.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.36,0:09:15.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Again, instead of fighting over the matter,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.62,0:09:19.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Isaac moves and finally finds a place
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.87,0:09:23.83,Default,,0,0,0,,where he can reside in peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:23.83,0:09:28.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob saw that his father’s peaceful actions
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.21,0:09:30.21,Default,,0,0,0,,had a good effect,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.22,0:09:34.81,Default,,0,0,0,,and he knew that Isaac\Nhad received Jehovah’s blessing.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.68,0:09:38.14,Default,,0,0,0,,What’s the lesson?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:38.14,0:09:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Parents, never underestimate\Nthe powerful effect
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.15,0:09:47.61,Default,,0,0,0,,your good example can have on your children.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.11,0:09:52.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob has a twin brother, Esau.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.74,0:09:56.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Of the two, Esau is born first,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.37,0:10:00.58,Default,,0,0,0,,but Jehovah foretells\Nthat—contrary to custom—
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.58,0:10:04.83,Default,,0,0,0,,the older Esau will serve\Nhis younger brother.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:05.71,0:10:10.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah foresees\Nwhat kind of personalities they’ll develop,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.34,0:10:14.47,Default,,0,0,0,,and he knows that Esau\Nwill have little appreciation
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.47,0:10:16.76,Default,,0,0,0,,for spiritual matters.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.76,0:10:19.01,Default,,0,0,0,,This becomes evident
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.01,0:10:22.97,Default,,0,0,0,,when Esau exchanges his right as firstborn
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.98,0:10:26.32,Default,,0,0,0,,for a mere bowl of stew,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.31,0:10:29.27,Default,,0,0,0,,sealing the matter with an oath.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.19,0:10:32.94,Default,,0,0,0,,But something more is involved.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.94,0:10:37.86,Default,,0,0,0,,In selling the birthright,\Nhe also gives up the right
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.87,0:10:42.58,Default,,0,0,0,,to receive a prophetic blessing\Nfrom his father.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.58,0:10:47.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Years pass, Isaac has grown old,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.46,0:10:49.96,Default,,0,0,0,,and he decides it’s time to impart
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.96,0:10:52.63,Default,,0,0,0,,the blessing to his firstborn.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.63,0:10:57.09,Default,,0,0,0,,He may not know\Nthat Esau had sold his right as firstborn.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:57.89,0:11:02.77,Default,,0,0,0,,In any case, he tells Esau\Nthat he will bless him
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.77,0:11:04.77,Default,,0,0,0,,but asks him first
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.77,0:11:08.07,Default,,0,0,0,,to provide him with a tasty dish
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.06,0:11:10.90,Default,,0,0,0,,of fresh game from the field.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.94,0:11:16.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Rebekah, the twins’ mother,\Noverhears this conversation
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.95,0:11:21.70,Default,,0,0,0,,and persuades Jacob\Nto impersonate his twin brother
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.70,0:11:24.37,Default,,0,0,0,,while Esau is out hunting.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.37,0:11:27.12,Default,,0,0,0,,The plan is successful.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.12,0:11:31.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Isaac unwittingly blesses Jacob!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:31.29,0:11:35.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Esau, at learning of this, is furious.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.55,0:11:37.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s take up the account
Dialogue: 0,0:11:37.55,0:11:41.68,Default,,0,0,0,,from Genesis 27:41.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:42.76,0:11:47.68,Default,,0,0,0,,“However, Esau harbored\Nanimosity against Jacob
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.69,0:11:51.28,Default,,0,0,0,,“because of the blessing\Nhis father had given him,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:51.27,0:11:54.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“and Esau kept saying in his heart:
Dialogue: 0,0:11:54.40,0:11:59.41,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘The days of mourning for my father\Nare getting closer.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:59.41,0:12:04.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“After that I am going to kill\NJacob my brother.’
Dialogue: 0,0:12:03.99,0:12:08.37,Default,,0,0,0,,“When the words of her older son Esau\Nwere told to Rebekah,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.37,0:12:11.87,Default,,0,0,0,,“she at once sent for her younger son Jacob
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.88,0:12:14.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“and said to him: ‘Look!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.63,0:12:19.09,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Your brother Esau is planning\Nto take revenge by killing you.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.09,0:12:21.80,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Now, my son, do as I say.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.80,0:12:25.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Get up and run away\Nto my brother Laban at Haran.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:25.72,0:12:28.22,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Dwell with him for a while
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.23,0:12:31.65,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘until your brother’s rage calms down,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.65,0:12:35.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘until your brother’s anger\Ntoward you subsides
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.32,0:12:38.70,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and he forgets what you have done to him.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.70,0:12:41.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Then I will send for you from there.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.74,0:12:46.08,Default,,0,0,0,,“Why should I lose both of you in one day?’
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.08,0:12:50.46,Default,,0,0,0,,“After that Rebekah kept saying to Isaac:
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.46,0:12:55.34,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I am disgusted with my life\Nbecause of the daughters of Heth.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.34,0:12:58.55,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘If Jacob ever takes a wife\Nfrom the daughters of Heth,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.55,0:13:00.55,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘like these daughters of the land,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.55,0:13:03.47,Default,,0,0,0,,“what good is my life?’
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.47,0:13:05.60,Default,,0,0,0,,“So Isaac called Jacob
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.60,0:13:09.48,Default,,0,0,0,,“and blessed him and commanded him, saying:
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.48,0:13:13.15,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘You must not take a wife\Nfrom the daughters of Canaan.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.15,0:13:15.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Go away to Paddanaram
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.44,0:13:18.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘to the house of Bethuel,\Nyour mother’s father,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.32,0:13:21.03,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and from there take for yourself a wife
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.03,0:13:24.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘from the daughters of Laban,\Nyour mother’s brother.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.78,0:13:29.79,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘God Almighty will bless you\Nand make you fruitful and multiply you,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:29.79,0:13:33.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and you will certainly become\Na congregation of peoples.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.58,0:13:36.92,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘And he will give to you\Nthe blessing of Abraham,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.92,0:13:39.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘to you and to your offspring with you,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.51,0:13:44.43,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘so that you may take possession of the land\Nwhere you have been living as a foreigner,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.43,0:13:47.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“which God has given to Abraham.’
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.51,0:13:50.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“So Isaac sent Jacob away,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.52,0:13:52.98,Default,,0,0,0,,“and he departed for Paddanaram,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.98,0:13:56.48,Default,,0,0,0,,“to Laban the son of Bethuel the Aramaean,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:56.48,0:14:00.53,Default,,0,0,0,,the brother of Rebekah,\Nthe mother of Jacob and Esau.”
Dialogue: 0,0:14:01.74,0:14:06.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob’s parents tell him to travel\Nto his uncle, Laban,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:06.37,0:14:08.54,Default,,0,0,0,,to find a wife.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.54,0:14:11.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, the core issue
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.08,0:14:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,is the problem with Esau.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.00,0:14:18.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Recall that earlier,\NIsaac had a problem with the Philistines
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.75,0:14:23.55,Default,,0,0,0,,—a problem that evidently\Ncould not be settled peacefully.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:23.55,0:14:26.64,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what did Isaac do?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.64,0:14:29.31,Default,,0,0,0,,He moved on.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.31,0:14:33.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Now Jacob faces a similar situation.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.06,0:14:36.11,Default,,0,0,0,,His brother is seething with anger,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.81,0:14:39.94,Default,,0,0,0,,so Jacob leaves.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.94,0:14:43.44,Default,,0,0,0,,It means leaving his home and his family;
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.45,0:14:48.04,Default,,0,0,0,,it means making a long journey\Nto a distant land.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.08,0:14:52.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob could have chosen to stand his ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.79,0:14:55.29,Default,,0,0,0,,He owns the birthright.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.29,0:14:58.38,Default,,0,0,0,,He could argue the matter\Nwith his father and mother:
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.38,0:15:02.01,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I’m no child. I’m 77 years old!’
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.05,0:15:06.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob does none of those things.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.01,0:15:08.26,Default,,0,0,0,,The Bible simply says:
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.26,0:15:12.10,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jacob obeyed his father and his mother
Dialogue: 0,0:15:12.10,0:15:14.23,Default,,0,0,0,,and departed.”
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.23,0:15:16.61,Default,,0,0,0,,What’s the lesson?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.60,0:15:18.85,Default,,0,0,0,,When we face a situation
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.86,0:15:22.07,Default,,0,0,0,,that can’t be settled peacefully,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.07,0:15:27.08,Default,,0,0,0,,we probably won’t need to flee for our lives\Nto a distant land.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.07,0:15:31.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes, however,\Nit is the course of wisdom
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.03,0:15:35.12,Default,,0,0,0,,to walk away from a situation.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:35.12,0:15:39.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Proverbs 17:14 says:
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.50,0:15:44.42,Default,,0,0,0,,“Beginning a fight\Nis like opening a floodgate;
Dialogue: 0,0:15:44.42,0:15:48.17,Default,,0,0,0,,before the quarrel breaks out,\Ntake your leave.”
Dialogue: 0,0:15:50.01,0:15:53.35,Default,,0,0,0,,While Jacob is on his way to his uncle,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.35,0:15:56.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah appears to Jacob in a dream
Dialogue: 0,0:15:56.68,0:16:01.27,Default,,0,0,0,,and assures him\Nof his support and protection.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.07,0:16:04.07,Default,,0,0,0,,That does not mean
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.07,0:16:07.20,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jacob’s troubles are over.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.20,0:16:11.96,Default,,0,0,0,,At the journey’s end,\Nhe moves in with his uncle’s household.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.95,0:16:16.12,Default,,0,0,0,,In time, a situation arises again
Dialogue: 0,0:16:16.12,0:16:18.12,Default,,0,0,0,,that shows that Jacob
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.12,0:16:21.54,Default,,0,0,0,,is a man who loves peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.54,0:16:26.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s read about it from Genesis 29:16.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.76,0:16:31.39,Default,,0,0,0,,“Now Laban had two daughters.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.39,0:16:33.85,Default,,0,0,0,,“The name of the older was Leah,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:33.85,0:16:37.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“and the name of the younger, Rachel.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.18,0:16:40.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“But the eyes of Leah had no luster,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:40.52,0:16:42.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“whereas Rachel had become
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.52,0:16:46.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“a very attractive and beautiful woman.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.19,0:16:50.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jacob had fallen in love with Rachel,\Nso he said:
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.45,0:16:53.16,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I am willing to serve you seven years
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.16,0:16:55.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“for your younger daughter Rachel.’
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.74,0:16:58.03,Default,,0,0,0,,“To this Laban said:
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.04,0:17:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘It is better for me to give her to you\Nthan to give her to another man.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:03.00,0:17:05.09,Default,,0,0,0,,“Keep dwelling with me.’
Dialogue: 0,0:17:05.09,0:17:08.93,Default,,0,0,0,,“And Jacob served seven years for Rachel,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:08.92,0:17:13.09,Default,,0,0,0,,“but in his eyes\Nthey were like just a few days
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.09,0:17:15.68,Default,,0,0,0,,“because of his love for her.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.68,0:17:18.77,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then Jacob said to Laban:
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.77,0:17:22.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Give over my wife because my days are up,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:22.40,0:17:24.94,Default,,0,0,0,,“and let me have relations with her.’
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.94,0:17:28.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“With that Laban gathered\Nall the men of the place
Dialogue: 0,0:17:28.69,0:17:30.73,Default,,0,0,0,,“and made a feast.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.74,0:17:35.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“But during the evening,\Nhe resorted to taking his daughter Leah
Dialogue: 0,0:17:35.74,0:17:40.58,Default,,0,0,0,,“and bringing her to him\Nthat he might have relations with her.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:40.58,0:17:44.25,Default,,0,0,0,,“Laban also gave his female servant Zilpah
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.25,0:17:47.30,Default,,0,0,0,,“to his daughter Leah as a servant.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.30,0:17:52.31,Default,,0,0,0,,“In the morning Jacob saw that it was Leah!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.30,0:17:54.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“So he said to Laban:
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.51,0:17:56.55,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘What have you done to me?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:56.55,0:17:59.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Was it not for Rachel that I served you?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.18,0:18:01.68,Default,,0,0,0,,“Why have you tricked me?’
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.68,0:18:04.02,Default,,0,0,0,,“To this Laban said:
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.02,0:18:09.03,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘It is not our custom here to give\Nthe younger woman before the firstborn.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.03,0:18:11.87,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Celebrate the week of this woman.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:11.86,0:18:14.61,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘After that you will also be given\Nthis other woman
Dialogue: 0,0:18:14.61,0:18:19.07,Default,,0,0,0,,“in exchange for serving me\Nseven more years.’
Dialogue: 0,0:18:19.08,0:18:23.25,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jacob did so\Nand celebrated the week of this woman,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:23.25,0:18:27.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“after which he gave him\Nhis daughter Rachel as a wife.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.63,0:18:31.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“Besides, Laban gave\Nhis female servant Bilhah
Dialogue: 0,0:18:31.17,0:18:34.05,Default,,0,0,0,,to his daughter Rachel as her servant.”
Dialogue: 0,0:18:35.47,0:18:38.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob has reason to be upset.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:38.81,0:18:40.81,Default,,0,0,0,,He had arranged with Laban
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.81,0:18:44.52,Default,,0,0,0,,to work seven years for Rachel.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:44.52,0:18:47.19,Default,,0,0,0,,At the end of the seven years,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.19,0:18:49.78,Default,,0,0,0,,a wedding feast is arranged.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.77,0:18:53.15,Default,,0,0,0,,But the heavily-veiled woman\Nbrought in to him
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.15,0:18:55.19,Default,,0,0,0,,is not Rachel;
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.20,0:18:57.45,Default,,0,0,0,,it’s Leah!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.45,0:19:02.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Imagine how shocked Jacob must have been!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.08,0:19:04.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead of admitting to his deceit,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:04.91,0:19:08.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Laban gives an excuse.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.33,0:19:11.54,Default,,0,0,0,,What thoughts come to Jacob’s mind?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.55,0:19:16.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Does he consider that Jehovah\Nmight be working out his promise
Dialogue: 0,0:19:16.09,0:19:18.93,Default,,0,0,0,,to make Jacob’s offspring plentiful
Dialogue: 0,0:19:18.93,0:19:22.14,Default,,0,0,0,,“like the dust particles of the earth”?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:22.14,0:19:24.31,Default,,0,0,0,,We don’t know.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:24.31,0:19:29.27,Default,,0,0,0,,As it turns out,\NLeah bears him six sons,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.27,0:19:32.48,Default,,0,0,0,,including Levi and Judah
Dialogue: 0,0:19:32.48,0:19:37.36,Default,,0,0,0,,—family heads of the two\Nmost honored tribes of Israel.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.24,0:19:41.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course,\NJacob couldn’t have foreknown this.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.74,0:19:45.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, Jacob the peacemaker
Dialogue: 0,0:19:45.41,0:19:47.41,Default,,0,0,0,,accepts Leah
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.42,0:19:51.67,Default,,0,0,0,,and goes along\Nwith Laban’s outrageous request
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.67,0:19:55.88,Default,,0,0,0,,that he work an additional seven years\Nfor Rachel.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:57.18,0:19:59.60,Default,,0,0,0,,What’s the lesson?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.59,0:20:02.13,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s disappointing when others
Dialogue: 0,0:20:02.14,0:20:05.23,Default,,0,0,0,,don’t hold to their agreements.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:05.22,0:20:09.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Like Jacob, can we find it in our hearts
Dialogue: 0,0:20:09.65,0:20:14.61,Default,,0,0,0,,to forgive and find a way\Nto preserve peace with them?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:16.44,0:20:18.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob serves Laban
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.45,0:20:21.75,Default,,0,0,0,,for 14 years for his two wives,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.74,0:20:25.08,Default,,0,0,0,,and he works for Laban another 6 years
Dialogue: 0,0:20:25.08,0:20:27.83,Default,,0,0,0,,for a flock of his own.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.83,0:20:31.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, at Jehovah’s direction,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.08,0:20:34.92,Default,,0,0,0,,he gathers his family along with his animals
Dialogue: 0,0:20:34.92,0:20:39.22,Default,,0,0,0,,and, without informing Laban,\Nhe leaves for home.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:40.34,0:20:44.34,Default,,0,0,0,,When Laban learns of this, he is furious!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.35,0:20:47.52,Default,,0,0,0,,He chases and catches up with Jacob.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.56,0:20:51.15,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a dangerous situation,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:51.15,0:20:54.49,Default,,0,0,0,,one that can easily turn violent.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.36,0:20:58.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Imagine how it might have been:
Dialogue: 0,0:20:58.19,0:21:01.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob had come to a mountainous region.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.82,0:21:06.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Possibly it’s morning, and the air is cool.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:06.20,0:21:09.33,Default,,0,0,0,,There are the sounds and smells of animals
Dialogue: 0,0:21:09.33,0:21:14.34,Default,,0,0,0,,—sheep, donkeys, camels; there are many.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.34,0:21:16.72,Default,,0,0,0,,The servants attend to them,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.71,0:21:20.38,Default,,0,0,0,,getting them ready for the day’s journey.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:20.38,0:21:23.76,Default,,0,0,0,,But then come cries of alarm.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.76,0:21:27.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Laban has come, and he’s not alone.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:27.10,0:21:29.77,Default,,0,0,0,,He arrives with strong men.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:29.77,0:21:34.07,Default,,0,0,0,,They gallop in on camels; they dismount.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.06,0:21:38.23,Default,,0,0,0,,This is not a friendly visit.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.23,0:21:42.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Laban’s men are ready\Nto obey orders from Laban.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:42.86,0:21:46.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob’s servants quickly gather to the scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:46.45,0:21:50.62,Default,,0,0,0,,All eyes are fixed on Laban and Jacob,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:50.62,0:21:52.62,Default,,0,0,0,,who argue.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:52.62,0:21:56.96,Default,,0,0,0,,The previous night,\NJehovah had warned Laban in a dream
Dialogue: 0,0:21:56.96,0:22:01.13,Default,,0,0,0,,to be careful about what he’d say to Jacob.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:01.13,0:22:05.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, Laban is angry and aggressive.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:07.05,0:22:09.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Laban makes two charges.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:09.68,0:22:14.64,Default,,0,0,0,,First, he says:\N“Why have you resorted to outwitting me
Dialogue: 0,0:22:14.65,0:22:18.24,Default,,0,0,0,,“and carrying my daughters off like captives
Dialogue: 0,0:22:18.23,0:22:20.23,Default,,0,0,0,,“taken by the sword?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:20.23,0:22:22.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“Why did you run away secretly
Dialogue: 0,0:22:22.57,0:22:25.62,Default,,0,0,0,,and outwit me and not tell me?”
Dialogue: 0,0:22:26.82,0:22:29.66,Default,,0,0,0,,The answer to that charge is obvious.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.66,0:22:31.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob replies:
Dialogue: 0,0:22:31.91,0:22:34.41,Default,,0,0,0,,“It was because I was afraid,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:34.42,0:22:36.55,Default,,0,0,0,,“for I said to myself,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.54,0:22:40.17,Default,,0,0,0,,‘You might take your daughters\Naway from me by force.’”
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.01,0:22:44.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Laban also charges that Jacob has stolen
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.68,0:22:47.18,Default,,0,0,0,,his household gods.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:47.18,0:22:50.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Rachel has indeed stolen the gods,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:50.64,0:22:53.94,Default,,0,0,0,,but Jacob knows nothing about this.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.94,0:22:58.90,Default,,0,0,0,,A search is made,\Nbut the idols are not found.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.90,0:23:01.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob then makes his defense.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:01.57,0:23:03.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s take up our reading
Dialogue: 0,0:23:03.57,0:23:07.32,Default,,0,0,0,,at Genesis 31:36.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:09.24,0:23:12.62,Default,,0,0,0,,“At that Jacob became angry
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.62,0:23:15.33,Default,,0,0,0,,“and began to criticize Laban.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:15.33,0:23:17.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jacob then said to Laban:
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.96,0:23:22.97,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘What is my offense, and for what sin\Nare you hotly pursuing me?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.96,0:23:25.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Now that you have searched\Nthrough all my goods,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:25.97,0:23:28.93,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘what have you found\Nthat belongs to your house?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.93,0:23:32.23,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Put it here in front of my brothers\Nand your brothers,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:32.22,0:23:35.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and let them decide between the two of us.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.89,0:23:39.19,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘During these 20 years\Nthat I have been with you,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:39.19,0:23:42.53,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘your sheep and your goats never miscarried,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.53,0:23:46.12,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and I never ate the rams of your flock.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.11,0:23:50.11,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I did not bring you any animal\Ntorn by wild beasts.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:50.12,0:23:53.16,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I would stand the loss of it myself.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:53.16,0:23:57.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Whether the animal was stolen by day\Nor was stolen by night,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.75,0:24:00.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘you would demand compensation from me.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:00.96,0:24:05.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘By day the heat consumed me,\Nand the cold by night,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:05.72,0:24:08.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and sleep would flee from my eyes.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.72,0:24:13.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘This makes 20 years for me in your house.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:13.18,0:24:16.73,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I have served you 14 years\Nfor your two daughters
Dialogue: 0,0:24:16.73,0:24:19.15,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and 6 years for your flock,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.15,0:24:23.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and you kept changing my wages ten times.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:23.19,0:24:26.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘If the God of my father, the God of Abraham
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.69,0:24:28.98,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and the One whom Isaac fears,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:28.99,0:24:31.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘had not been on my side,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.78,0:24:35.53,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘you would now have sent me away\Nempty-handed.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.54,0:24:39.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘God has seen my affliction\Nand the toil of my hands,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:39.62,0:24:42.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“and that is why he reproved you last night.’
Dialogue: 0,0:24:42.96,0:24:45.38,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then Laban answered Jacob:
Dialogue: 0,0:24:45.38,0:24:49.68,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘The daughters are my daughters\Nand the children my children
Dialogue: 0,0:24:49.68,0:24:51.93,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and the flock my flock,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:51.93,0:24:54.56,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and everything you are looking at
Dialogue: 0,0:24:54.56,0:24:58.48,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘is mine and my daughters’.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:58.48,0:25:02.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘What can I do today against these\Nor against their children
Dialogue: 0,0:25:02.56,0:25:04.81,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘whom they have borne?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.82,0:25:09.16,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Now come, let us make a covenant,\Nyou and I,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:09.15,0:25:12.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“and it will serve as a witness between us.’
Dialogue: 0,0:25:12.20,0:25:17.16,Default,,0,0,0,,“So Jacob took a stone\Nand set it up as a pillar.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:17.16,0:25:21.66,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then Jacob said to his brothers:\N‘Pick up stones!’
Dialogue: 0,0:25:21.67,0:25:24.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“And they took stones and made a pile.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:24.88,0:25:29.76,Default,,0,0,0,,“After that they ate there\Non the pile of stones.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.76,0:25:33.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“And Laban began calling it Jegarsahadutha,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:33.51,0:25:36.43,Default,,0,0,0,,“but Jacob called it Galeed.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:36.43,0:25:38.43,Default,,0,0,0,,“Laban then said:
Dialogue: 0,0:25:38.43,0:25:41.06,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘This pile of stones is a witness
Dialogue: 0,0:25:41.06,0:25:44.11,Default,,0,0,0,,“between me and you today.’
Dialogue: 0,0:25:44.11,0:25:47.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“That is why he named it Galeed,\Nand the Watchtower,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:47.86,0:25:49.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“for he said:
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.86,0:25:53.53,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Let Jehovah keep watch between you and me
Dialogue: 0,0:25:53.53,0:25:56.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘when we are out of each other’s sight.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.33,0:25:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘If you mistreat my daughters
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.99,0:26:02.91,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and if you start taking wives\Nin addition to my daughters,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:02.92,0:26:05.21,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘though there is no man with us,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:05.21,0:26:09.97,Default,,0,0,0,,“remember that God will be a witness\Nbetween you and me.’
Dialogue: 0,0:26:09.96,0:26:13.26,Default,,0,0,0,,“Laban went on to say to Jacob:
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.26,0:26:15.97,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Here is this pile of stones,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:15.97,0:26:20.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and here is the pillar\Nthat I have erected between you and me.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:20.52,0:26:23.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘This pile of stones is a witness,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:23.56,0:26:26.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and the pillar\Nis something that bears witness,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:26.40,0:26:30.82,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘that I will not pass beyond this pile\Nof stones to bring harm to you
Dialogue: 0,0:26:30.82,0:26:34.24,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and you will not pass\Nbeyond this pile of stones
Dialogue: 0,0:26:34.24,0:26:37.24,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and this pillar to bring harm to me.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:37.24,0:26:40.70,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Let the God of Abraham\Nand the God of Nahor,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:40.70,0:26:45.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“the God of their father, judge between us.’
Dialogue: 0,0:26:45.21,0:26:47.38,Default,,0,0,0,,“And Jacob swore by the One
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.38,0:26:50.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“whom his father Isaac fears.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:50.88,0:26:55.43,Default,,0,0,0,,“After that Jacob offered\Na sacrifice in the mountain
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.43,0:26:58.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“and invited his brothers to eat bread.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:58.64,0:27:02.90,Default,,0,0,0,,“So they ate\Nand spent the night in the mountain.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:02.89,0:27:06.10,Default,,0,0,0,,“However, Laban got up early in the morning
Dialogue: 0,0:27:06.10,0:27:10.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“and kissed his grandchildren\Nand his daughters and blessed them.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:10.69,0:27:14.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Then Laban departed and returned home.”
Dialogue: 0,0:27:17.07,0:27:21.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob had served Laban faithfully\Nfor 20 years,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:21.87,0:27:26.50,Default,,0,0,0,,even though Laban had defrauded\Nand exploited him.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:26.50,0:27:28.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Laban doesn’t acknowledge that
Dialogue: 0,0:27:28.58,0:27:31.04,Default,,0,0,0,,but, rather, dishonestly claims
Dialogue: 0,0:27:31.05,0:27:33.30,Default,,0,0,0,,that he is the rightful owner
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.30,0:27:36.43,Default,,0,0,0,,of all that Jacob has with him.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:36.43,0:27:41.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Laban then suggests\Nthat they make a covenant of peace
Dialogue: 0,0:27:41.01,0:27:45.47,Default,,0,0,0,,ensuring that neither family\Nwill bring harm to the other.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.35,0:27:50.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Laban’s motive is not that he loves peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.40,0:27:54.40,Default,,0,0,0,,It might have been to ensure\Nthat Jacob will not return
Dialogue: 0,0:27:54.40,0:27:57.57,Default,,0,0,0,,with the household gods after Laban’s death
Dialogue: 0,0:27:57.57,0:28:01.45,Default,,0,0,0,,to deprive his sons of their inheritance.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.45,0:28:05.00,Default,,0,0,0,,In any case, Jacob agrees;
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.00,0:28:07.55,Default,,0,0,0,,everyone relaxes;
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.54,0:28:09.83,Default,,0,0,0,,there’s to be no violence.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:09.83,0:28:14.46,Default,,0,0,0,,And a monument is set up\Nto memorialize the agreement.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:15.38,0:28:19.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Despite the many years of oppression,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:19.05,0:28:22.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob agrees to a covenant of peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:22.97,0:28:27.39,Default,,0,0,0,,He does not harbor resentment\Nor seek revenge.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.56,0:28:32.44,Default,,0,0,0,,That crisis is over for Jacob.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:32.44,0:28:35.78,Default,,0,0,0,,But now another one looms.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:35.78,0:28:39.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob sends messengers to his brother.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:39.49,0:28:42.70,Default,,0,0,0,,They say that Jacob is returning
Dialogue: 0,0:28:42.70,0:28:45.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and that he seeks Esau’s favor.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:46.25,0:28:51.26,Default,,0,0,0,,The messengers return with the news\Nthat Esau is on his way to meet him
Dialogue: 0,0:28:51.25,0:28:54.71,Default,,0,0,0,,and with him are 400 men.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:54.71,0:28:56.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, my!
Dialogue: 0,0:28:56.76,0:28:59.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Is Esau still angry?
Dialogue: 0,0:28:59.72,0:29:02.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Understandably, Jacob is worried.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:02.93,0:29:06.56,Default,,0,0,0,,He does not want to fight with his brother.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:06.56,0:29:09.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Let us see how he handles the situation.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.60,0:29:14.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Please turn to Genesis 32:13.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:17.36,0:29:20.16,Default,,0,0,0,,“And he spent the night there.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:20.15,0:29:22.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then he took some of his possessions
Dialogue: 0,0:29:22.57,0:29:25.99,Default,,0,0,0,,“as a gift for Esau his brother:
Dialogue: 0,0:29:25.99,0:29:30.87,Default,,0,0,0,,“200 female goats, 20 male goats,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:30.87,0:29:34.62,Default,,0,0,0,,“200 female sheep, 20 rams,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.63,0:29:37.84,Default,,0,0,0,,“30 camels nursing their young,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:37.84,0:29:41.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“40 cows, 10 bulls,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.18,0:29:43.43,Default,,0,0,0,,“20 female donkeys
Dialogue: 0,0:29:43.43,0:29:47.27,Default,,0,0,0,,“and 10 full-grown male donkeys.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:47.26,0:29:50.14,Default,,0,0,0,,“He handed them over to his servants,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:50.14,0:29:52.39,Default,,0,0,0,,“one drove after another,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.39,0:29:55.02,Default,,0,0,0,,“and he said to his servants:
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.02,0:29:57.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Cross over ahead of me,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:57.44,0:30:02.24,Default,,0,0,0,,“and you are to set a space\Nbetween one drove and the next.’
Dialogue: 0,0:30:02.24,0:30:05.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“He also commanded the first one:
Dialogue: 0,0:30:05.20,0:30:08.91,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘In case Esau my brother\Nshould meet you and ask,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:08.91,0:30:12.16,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘“To whom do you belong,\Nand where are you going,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:12.16,0:30:15.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and to whom do these ahead of you belong?”
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.00,0:30:19.13,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘then you should say,\N“To your servant Jacob.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:19.13,0:30:22.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘“It is a gift sent to my lord, to Esau,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.72,0:30:26.97,Default,,0,0,0,,“and look! he himself is also behind us.”’
Dialogue: 0,0:30:26.97,0:30:30.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“And he commanded also the second, the third,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:30.18,0:30:33.39,Default,,0,0,0,,“and all those following the droves:
Dialogue: 0,0:30:33.39,0:30:35.43,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘According to this word,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:35.44,0:30:38.65,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘you are to speak to Esau when you meet him.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:38.65,0:30:41.24,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘And you should also say,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:41.24,0:30:45.04,Default,,0,0,0,,““Here is your servant Jacob behind us.”’
Dialogue: 0,0:30:45.03,0:30:47.53,Default,,0,0,0,,“For he said to himself:
Dialogue: 0,0:30:47.53,0:30:52.08,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘If I appease him\Nby sending a gift ahead of me,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:52.08,0:30:54.83,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘then afterward when I see him,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:54.83,0:30:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,he may give me a kindly reception.’”
Dialogue: 0,0:30:59.80,0:31:03.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob wants peaceful relations\Nwith his brother.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.80,0:31:08.39,Default,,0,0,0,,He sends a generous gift\N—hundreds of animals—
Dialogue: 0,0:31:08.39,0:31:10.85,Default,,0,0,0,,to help make that possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:10.85,0:31:13.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Was Jacob weak-minded,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:13.02,0:31:16.36,Default,,0,0,0,,too cowardly to stand up to his brother?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:16.35,0:31:17.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Not at all!
Dialogue: 0,0:31:17.94,0:31:20.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Why, as the time neared\Nfor the meeting with Esau,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:20.65,0:31:24.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob wrestles with an angel until dawn
Dialogue: 0,0:31:24.28,0:31:28.70,Default,,0,0,0,,to receive further assurance\Nof Jehovah’s blessing.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:28.70,0:31:33.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s now see what happens\Nwhen the two brothers meet.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:34.20,0:31:38.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Please turn to Genesis 33:1.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:40.13,0:31:43.05,Default,,0,0,0,,“Now Jacob raised his eyes
Dialogue: 0,0:31:43.05,0:31:45.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“and saw Esau coming,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:45.72,0:31:49.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“and 400 men were with him.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:49.18,0:31:53.10,Default,,0,0,0,,“So he divided the children\Namong Leah, Rachel,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:53.10,0:31:55.94,Default,,0,0,0,,“and the two female servants.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:55.93,0:32:00.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“He put the female servants\Nand their children in front,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:00.65,0:32:03.65,Default,,0,0,0,,“Leah and her children after them,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:03.65,0:32:06.90,Default,,0,0,0,,“and Rachel and Joseph behind them.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:06.90,0:32:09.82,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then he himself went ahead of them
Dialogue: 0,0:32:09.82,0:32:13.41,Default,,0,0,0,,“and bowed down to the earth seven times
Dialogue: 0,0:32:13.41,0:32:16.50,Default,,0,0,0,,“as he came near to his brother.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:16.50,0:32:19.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“But Esau ran to meet him,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:19.63,0:32:22.67,Default,,0,0,0,,“and he embraced him and kissed him,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:22.67,0:32:26.09,Default,,0,0,0,,“and they burst into tears.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:26.09,0:32:30.47,Default,,0,0,0,,“When he raised his eyes\Nand saw the women and the children,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:30.47,0:32:33.60,Default,,0,0,0,,“he said: ‘Who are these with you?’
Dialogue: 0,0:32:33.60,0:32:35.60,Default,,0,0,0,,“To which he said:
Dialogue: 0,0:32:35.60,0:32:39.65,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘The children with whom God\Nhas favored your servant.’
Dialogue: 0,0:32:39.65,0:32:44.49,Default,,0,0,0,,“At that the female servants\Ncame forward with their children
Dialogue: 0,0:32:44.48,0:32:46.48,Default,,0,0,0,,“and bowed down,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:46.49,0:32:49.74,Default,,0,0,0,,“and Leah too came forward with her children,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:49.74,0:32:51.95,Default,,0,0,0,,“and they bowed down.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:51.95,0:32:55.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then Joseph came forward with Rachel,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:55.20,0:32:57.33,Default,,0,0,0,,“and they bowed down.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:57.33,0:32:59.33,Default,,0,0,0,,“Esau said:
Dialogue: 0,0:32:59.33,0:33:03.33,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘What is the purpose of all this camp\Nof travelers that I have met?’
Dialogue: 0,0:33:03.34,0:33:06.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“He replied: ‘In order to find favor
Dialogue: 0,0:33:06.63,0:33:08.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“in the eyes of my lord.’
Dialogue: 0,0:33:08.72,0:33:10.81,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then Esau said:
Dialogue: 0,0:33:10.80,0:33:14.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I have a great many possessions,\Nmy brother.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:14.72,0:33:17.14,Default,,0,0,0,,“Keep what is yours.’
Dialogue: 0,0:33:17.14,0:33:19.48,Default,,0,0,0,,“However, Jacob said:
Dialogue: 0,0:33:19.48,0:33:22.02,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘No, please.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:22.02,0:33:25.48,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘If I have found favor in your eyes,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:25.48,0:33:28.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘you must take my gift from my hand,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:28.44,0:33:33.28,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘because I brought it\Nso that I could see your face.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:33.28,0:33:36.62,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘And I have seen your face
Dialogue: 0,0:33:36.62,0:33:39.04,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘as though seeing God’s face,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:39.04,0:33:42.04,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘in that you received me with pleasure.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:42.04,0:33:44.25,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Take, please,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:44.25,0:33:48.50,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘the gift conveying my blessing\Nthat was brought to you,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:48.51,0:33:51.39,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘for God has favored me
Dialogue: 0,0:33:51.38,0:33:55.01,Default,,0,0,0,,“and I have everything I need.’
Dialogue: 0,0:33:55.01,0:33:59.89,Default,,0,0,0,,And he continued to urge him,\Nso that he took it.”
Dialogue: 0,0:34:02.10,0:34:04.60,Default,,0,0,0,,What a happy outcome!
Dialogue: 0,0:34:04.61,0:34:07.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead of an angry confrontation,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:07.77,0:34:10.48,Default,,0,0,0,,there is a joyful reunion.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:10.49,0:34:14.29,Default,,0,0,0,,The two men shed tears; they embrace.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:14.28,0:34:18.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Again, Jacob is the peacemaker.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:18.87,0:34:21.21,Default,,0,0,0,,How did he prove that?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:21.20,0:34:25.41,Default,,0,0,0,,He prayed, and he acted in harmony\Nwith his prayers.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:25.42,0:34:27.17,Default,,0,0,0,,He sent gifts.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.17,0:34:31.67,Default,,0,0,0,,He showed honor and respect to his brother,\Ncalling him lord
Dialogue: 0,0:34:31.67,0:34:34.80,Default,,0,0,0,,and bowing seven times.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:34.80,0:34:37.09,Default,,0,0,0,,What’s the lesson?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:37.10,0:34:39.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Doesn’t this account well illustrate
Dialogue: 0,0:34:39.81,0:34:42.98,Default,,0,0,0,,the extent to which we\Nshould be willing to go
Dialogue: 0,0:34:42.98,0:34:47.23,Default,,0,0,0,,to preserve peace\Nwith our Christian brothers and sisters?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:48.57,0:34:50.82,Default,,0,0,0,,We learn so much
Dialogue: 0,0:34:50.82,0:34:53.82,Default,,0,0,0,,about seeking peace from Jacob.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:53.82,0:34:57.07,Default,,0,0,0,,When threatened by his brother\Nwhile living at home,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:57.07,0:34:59.07,Default,,0,0,0,,he moved away.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:59.08,0:35:03.17,Default,,0,0,0,,When deceived by Laban\Nregarding Rachel and Leah,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:03.16,0:35:05.29,Default,,0,0,0,,he yielded.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:05.29,0:35:08.67,Default,,0,0,0,,When chased down and accused by Laban,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:08.67,0:35:12.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob agreed to a covenant of peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:12.38,0:35:16.84,Default,,0,0,0,,And when confronting Esau, he offered a gift.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:16.84,0:35:18.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Keep in mind,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:18.47,0:35:20.60,Default,,0,0,0,,in none of these situations
Dialogue: 0,0:35:20.60,0:35:23.90,Default,,0,0,0,,was Jacob the one who needed to apologize.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:23.89,0:35:26.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet, throughout his life,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:26.44,0:35:29.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Jacob loved peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:29.82,0:35:32.74,Default,,0,0,0,,He relied on Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:32.73,0:35:35.48,Default,,0,0,0,,and Jehovah blessed him.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:35.49,0:35:38.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah never forgot Jacob
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.16,0:35:40.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and how he pursued peace
Dialogue: 0,0:35:40.83,0:35:43.46,Default,,0,0,0,,in his dealings with others.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:43.45,0:35:45.66,Default,,0,0,0,,When we do the same
Dialogue: 0,0:35:45.66,0:35:50.46,Default,,0,0,0,,—when we pursue peace\Nin the face of injustice,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:50.46,0:35:52.92,Default,,0,0,0,,in the face of persecution,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:52.92,0:35:57.05,Default,,0,0,0,,in small issues as well as in big issues—
Dialogue: 0,0:35:57.05,0:36:00.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah will not forget us either.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:00.18,0:36:02.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah will richly bless us
Dialogue: 0,0:36:02.64,0:36:04.77,Default,,0,0,0,,if we love peace
Dialogue: 0,0:36:04.77,0:36:08.69,Default,,0,0,0,,just as Jacob loved peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:15.69,0:36:17.90,Default,,0,0,0,,How comforting it is
Dialogue: 0,0:36:17.90,0:36:21.57,Default,,0,0,0,,to reflect on Jehovah’s love and support
Dialogue: 0,0:36:21.58,0:36:24.12,Default,,0,0,0,,for those who make peace!
Dialogue: 0,0:36:24.12,0:36:28.50,Default,,0,0,0,,This Bible account is filled\Nwith practical examples
Dialogue: 0,0:36:28.50,0:36:31.38,Default,,0,0,0,,that each of us can imitate.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:31.38,0:36:35.38,Default,,0,0,0,,You will be pleased to know\Nthat the dramatic Bible reading
Dialogue: 0,0:36:35.38,0:36:38.55,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jacob—A Man Who Loved Peace”
Dialogue: 0,0:36:38.55,0:36:41.05,Default,,0,0,0,,is now available for download
Dialogue: 0,0:36:41.05,0:36:43.93,Default,,0,0,0,,on the jw.org website
Dialogue: 0,0:36:43.93,0:36:47.14,Default,,0,0,0,,and in the {\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}JW Library® {\r} app.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:50.65,0:36:53.61,Default,,0,0,0,,How can we maintain our God-given peace
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.61,0:36:57.45,Default,,0,0,0,,despite living in an ungodly world?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:57.44,0:36:59.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Please pay close attention
Dialogue: 0,0:36:59.61,0:37:03.99,Default,,0,0,0,,to Brother David Schafer,\Na helper to the Teaching Committee,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:03.99,0:37:06.91,Default,,0,0,0,,as he answers this question in the talk
Dialogue: 0,0:37:06.91,0:37:10.91,Default,,0,0,0,,“The Result of True Righteousness\NWill Be Peace.”
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.22,0:37:23.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Earlier, we considered\Nthe expression at Philippians 4:7,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:23.14,0:37:27.60,Default,,0,0,0,,“the peace of God\Nthat surpasses all understanding,”
Dialogue: 0,0:37:27.60,0:37:30.77,Default,,0,0,0,,that is, the tranquility and calmness
Dialogue: 0,0:37:30.77,0:37:34.65,Default,,0,0,0,,we enjoy because we have\Na close friendship with Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:34.65,0:37:37.36,Default,,0,0,0,,What a remarkable blessing!
Dialogue: 0,0:37:37.36,0:37:40.61,Default,,0,0,0,,But although we enjoy God-given peace,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:40.61,0:37:45.28,Default,,0,0,0,,our life in this system of things\Nis not problem free, is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:45.28,0:37:48.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Psalm 34:19 acknowledges\Nas much when it says:
Dialogue: 0,0:37:48.75,0:37:52.80,Default,,0,0,0,,“Many are the hardships of the righteous one,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:52.79,0:37:56.84,Default,,0,0,0,,but Jehovah rescues him from them all.”
Dialogue: 0,0:37:58.05,0:38:00.64,Default,,0,0,0,,We may experience family opposition,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:00.63,0:38:03.63,Default,,0,0,0,,persecution, war, natural disasters,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:03.64,0:38:05.81,Default,,0,0,0,,or severe illnesses,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:05.80,0:38:10.14,Default,,0,0,0,,but none of these hardships\Ncan “separate us from God’s love.”
Dialogue: 0,0:38:10.14,0:38:12.31,Default,,0,0,0,,“Neither death nor life nor angels 
Dialogue: 0,0:38:12.31,0:38:14.77,Default,,0,0,0,,nor governments\Nnor things now here nor things to come”
Dialogue: 0,0:38:14.77,0:38:19.78,Default,,0,0,0,,—none of these things\Ncan rob us of the peace Jehovah gives.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:20.53,0:38:25.29,Default,,0,0,0,,And yet, there is something that can.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:26.32,0:38:31.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Please turn with me to Isaiah 32:17.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:31.33,0:38:33.33,Default,,0,0,0,,And as we read this text,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:33.33,0:38:37.92,Default,,0,0,0,,notice that it refers to peace as a result.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:37.92,0:38:41.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you think of peace that way, as a result?
Dialogue: 0,0:38:41.21,0:38:45.46,Default,,0,0,0,,If peace is a result, what causes it?
Dialogue: 0,0:38:45.47,0:38:49.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Isaiah 32:17:
Dialogue: 0,0:38:49.31,0:38:51.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“The result
Dialogue: 0,0:38:51.52,0:38:56.28,Default,,0,0,0,,“of true righteousness will be peace, 
Dialogue: 0,0:38:56.27,0:39:00.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“and the fruitage of true righteousness
Dialogue: 0,0:39:00.44,0:39:04.74,Default,,0,0,0,,will be lasting tranquility and security.”
Dialogue: 0,0:39:05.78,0:39:10.70,Default,,0,0,0,,What a beautiful expression,\N“lasting tranquility and security”!
Dialogue: 0,0:39:11.62,0:39:15.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Again, from what does it result?
Dialogue: 0,0:39:15.21,0:39:17.21,Default,,0,0,0,,True righteousness.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:17.21,0:39:19.63,Default,,0,0,0,,What if righteousness\Nno longer mattered to us?
Dialogue: 0,0:39:19.63,0:39:21.88,Default,,0,0,0,,What if a person concluded:\N‘It makes no difference
Dialogue: 0,0:39:21.88,0:39:23.97,Default,,0,0,0,,‘how I live or what sacrifices I make.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:23.97,0:39:25.97,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I’m going to suffer hardships either way.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:25.97,0:39:29.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I might as well do\Nwhatever I please while I can’?
Dialogue: 0,0:39:29.01,0:39:32.35,Default,,0,0,0,,What’s wrong with that thinking?
Dialogue: 0,0:39:32.35,0:39:36.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Would it show appreciation for peace
Dialogue: 0,0:39:36.14,0:39:38.98,Default,,0,0,0,,and all that Jehovah\Nhas done to make it possible?
Dialogue: 0,0:39:38.98,0:39:41.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Peace is a result.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:41.44,0:39:44.86,Default,,0,0,0,,And behind every result is a cause.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:44.86,0:39:49.41,Default,,0,0,0,,If we want peace,\Nwe have to pursue righteousness.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:49.41,0:39:53.54,Default,,0,0,0,,An unrighteous person\Ncannot be at peace with God.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:53.54,0:39:58.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Serious transgressions put a strain\Non a person’s relationship with God.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:58.08,0:40:00.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Recall King David’s words found
Dialogue: 0,0:40:00.46,0:40:03.17,Default,,0,0,0,,at Psalm 38:3.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:03.17,0:40:07.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Sensing Jehovah’s disapproval, he wrote:
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.55,0:40:10.14,Default,,0,0,0,,“There is no peace
Dialogue: 0,0:40:10.14,0:40:14.65,Default,,0,0,0,,within my bones because of my sin.”
Dialogue: 0,0:40:14.64,0:40:16.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Inevitably, the unrighteous person
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.94,0:40:21.32,Default,,0,0,0,,will reap what he sows and lose his peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:22.69,0:40:26.57,Default,,0,0,0,,What is righteousness,\Nand how do we pursue it?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:27.53,0:40:30.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Righteousness is what we have or what we show
Dialogue: 0,0:40:30.70,0:40:33.87,Default,,0,0,0,,when we do what is right\Naccording to Jehovah’s standards.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:33.87,0:40:36.75,Default,,0,0,0,,And those standards\Nare not just rules we follow
Dialogue: 0,0:40:36.75,0:40:40.92,Default,,0,0,0,,but principles that guide the way\Nwe deal with each other.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:40.92,0:40:43.88,Default,,0,0,0,,As Universal Sovereign and Creator,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:43.88,0:40:46.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah God determines what is righteous.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:46.63,0:40:48.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn’t that what was represented
Dialogue: 0,0:40:48.47,0:40:51.22,Default,,0,0,0,,by “the tree of the knowledge\Nof good and bad” in the garden of Eden?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:51.22,0:40:54.93,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result of Jehovah’s command\Nto abstain from its fruit,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:54.93,0:40:59.14,Default,,0,0,0,,that tree represented God’s right\Nto determine for his creatures
Dialogue: 0,0:40:59.14,0:41:02.14,Default,,0,0,0,,what is good and what is bad for them.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:02.15,0:41:05.45,Default,,0,0,0,,And although Jehovah\Nhas given humans free will,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:05.44,0:41:07.48,Default,,0,0,0,,the right to choose,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:07.49,0:41:10.45,Default,,0,0,0,,he has not granted humans\N(not even perfect ones)
Dialogue: 0,0:41:10.45,0:41:15.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the right to set the standard\Nfor what is righteous and what is not.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:15.87,0:41:20.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, notice once again that Isaiah 32:17 says
Dialogue: 0,0:41:20.67,0:41:25.68,Default,,0,0,0,,that “the result\Nof true righteousness will be peace.”
Dialogue: 0,0:41:25.67,0:41:29.63,Default,,0,0,0,,It uses that term twice—“true righteousness.”
Dialogue: 0,0:41:29.63,0:41:33.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Not everything called righteousness\Nis true righteousness.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:33.97,0:41:37.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Many people view righteousness\Nas just a personal virtue
Dialogue: 0,0:41:37.56,0:41:40.10,Default,,0,0,0,,achieved by following the rules.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:40.10,0:41:42.19,Default,,0,0,0,,At Matthew 23:28,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:42.19,0:41:46.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus said that the Pharisees\Nappeared righteous on the outside,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:46.27,0:41:49.02,Default,,0,0,0,,but inside they were lawless.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:49.99,0:41:53.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Ecclesiastes 7:16 talks about those
Dialogue: 0,0:41:53.11,0:41:57.41,Default,,0,0,0,,who think their standards\Nare more righteous even than God’s.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:57.41,0:41:59.45,Default,,0,0,0,,And at Romans 10:3,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:59.45,0:42:02.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul talked about people\Nwho ‘seek to establish
Dialogue: 0,0:42:02.50,0:42:05.54,Default,,0,0,0,,their own righteousness.’
Dialogue: 0,0:42:05.54,0:42:07.54,Default,,0,0,0,,But false piety,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:07.55,0:42:10.35,Default,,0,0,0,,over-righteousness, and self-righteousness
Dialogue: 0,0:42:10.34,0:42:14.68,Default,,0,0,0,,are not what Isaiah 32:17 is talking about.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:15.85,0:42:19.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Today, many argue for the acceptance
Dialogue: 0,0:42:19.31,0:42:22.02,Default,,0,0,0,,of conduct that Jehovah forbids.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:22.02,0:42:26.65,Default,,0,0,0,,They may even find support\Nfrom a world already alienated from God.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:27.86,0:42:31.07,Default,,0,0,0,,But wide acceptance in a growing community
Dialogue: 0,0:42:31.07,0:42:33.74,Default,,0,0,0,,does not redefine righteousness.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:33.74,0:42:37.20,Default,,0,0,0,,None of that is true righteousness.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:37.20,0:42:40.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Our loving Creator sets\Nthe standard for what is right
Dialogue: 0,0:42:40.29,0:42:44.29,Default,,0,0,0,,—not our feelings,\Nnot the community at large.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:44.29,0:42:46.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, while you’re here in Isaiah,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:46.84,0:42:49.18,Default,,0,0,0,,please turn to chapter 48.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:50.09,0:42:53.43,Default,,0,0,0,,In order to be viewed as righteous,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:53.43,0:42:56.89,Default,,0,0,0,,we have to trust that Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:42:56.89,0:42:59.10,Default,,0,0,0,,should set the standard of right and wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:59.10,0:43:02.27,Default,,0,0,0,,In addition, we must prove\Nby our speech and actions
Dialogue: 0,0:43:02.27,0:43:06.27,Default,,0,0,0,,that we agree with Jehovah’s standards\Nand obey him.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:06.27,0:43:10.65,Default,,0,0,0,,And that takes real courage\Nin a wicked world.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:10.65,0:43:13.78,Default,,0,0,0,,But when we do that, we enjoy the result.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:13.78,0:43:16.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice what it says at Isaiah chapter 48,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:16.66,0:43:19.08,Default,,0,0,0,,verses 17, 18:
Dialogue: 0,0:43:20.49,0:43:25.33,Default,,0,0,0,,“This is what Jehovah says, your Repurchaser,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:25.33,0:43:28.17,Default,,0,0,0,,“the Holy One of Israel:
Dialogue: 0,0:43:28.17,0:43:31.21,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I, Jehovah, am your God,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:31.21,0:43:34.38,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘the One teaching you to benefit yourself
Dialogue: 0,0:43:34.38,0:43:37.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘[or as the footnote says, teaching you\N“for your own good”],
Dialogue: 0,0:43:37.89,0:43:42.31,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘the One guiding you\Nin the way you should walk.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:42.31,0:43:46.48,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘If only you would pay attention\Nto my commandments!
Dialogue: 0,0:43:46.48,0:43:51.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Then your peace\Nwould become just like a river
Dialogue: 0,0:43:51.32,0:43:56.33,Default,,0,0,0,,and your righteousness\Nlike the waves of the sea.’”
Dialogue: 0,0:43:57.16,0:44:00.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Paying attention to Jehovah’s commandments\Nresults in two things.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:00.91,0:44:03.20,Default,,0,0,0,,First, our peace
Dialogue: 0,0:44:03.20,0:44:06.50,Default,,0,0,0,,will “become just like a river”
Dialogue: 0,0:44:06.50,0:44:10.13,Default,,0,0,0,,—serene, abundant, ongoing.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:10.13,0:44:14.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Second, our righteousness\Nwill be “like the waves of the sea.”
Dialogue: 0,0:44:15.59,0:44:17.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember your last trip to the beach?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:17.97,0:44:20.06,Default,,0,0,0,,As you stood there on the shore,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:20.05,0:44:22.43,Default,,0,0,0,,perhaps on a high hill overlooking the ocean
Dialogue: 0,0:44:22.43,0:44:26.23,Default,,0,0,0,,watching the waves\Nroll in one after the other
Dialogue: 0,0:44:26.23,0:44:28.77,Default,,0,0,0,,just as they have for thousands of years,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:28.77,0:44:32.19,Default,,0,0,0,,could you feel a sense of constancy?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:32.19,0:44:34.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah says that our course
Dialogue: 0,0:44:34.19,0:44:37.44,Default,,0,0,0,,of doing what is right can be just like that.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:37.45,0:44:40.08,Default,,0,0,0,,He will guide us\Nin the path of righteousness.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:40.07,0:44:43.16,Default,,0,0,0,,He will bless us with unending peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:43.16,0:44:48.00,Default,,0,0,0,,In the process, we learn through experience
Dialogue: 0,0:44:48.00,0:44:50.75,Default,,0,0,0,,how Jehovah’s wise and loving ways
Dialogue: 0,0:44:50.75,0:44:52.96,Default,,0,0,0,,truly benefit us personally.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:52.96,0:44:55.21,Default,,0,0,0,,But if we refuse to do that,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:55.21,0:44:58.30,Default,,0,0,0,,we learn what agitation\Nand discord truly mean.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:58.30,0:45:00.93,Default,,0,0,0,,As verse 22 says:
Dialogue: 0,0:45:00.93,0:45:05.77,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘There is no peace,’ says Jehovah,\N‘for the wicked.’”
Dialogue: 0,0:45:06.72,0:45:08.85,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s not a heavy-handed threat to manipulate
Dialogue: 0,0:45:08.85,0:45:11.23,Default,,0,0,0,,human behavior\Nas if Jehovah needed to do that.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:11.23,0:45:15.78,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s a fact, a truth, a timeless principle.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:15.78,0:45:17.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“God is love.”
Dialogue: 0,0:45:17.78,0:45:20.28,Default,,0,0,0,,He teaches us for our own good.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:20.28,0:45:25.24,Default,,0,0,0,,And the result if we pay attention is peace
Dialogue: 0,0:45:25.24,0:45:29.33,Default,,0,0,0,,—Isaiah 48:17, 18.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:29.33,0:45:32.92,Default,,0,0,0,,And these verses assure us\Nthat imperfect humans
Dialogue: 0,0:45:32.92,0:45:37.93,Default,,0,0,0,,truly can have a righteous standing with God.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:37.92,0:45:40.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s explore that further.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:40.59,0:45:43.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you recall the very first time
Dialogue: 0,0:45:43.68,0:45:47.48,Default,,0,0,0,,the word “righteous” is used in the Bible?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:47.47,0:45:50.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Turn with me, please, to Genesis chapter 6.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:50.64,0:45:53.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, you likely recognize this\Nas the account about Noah.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:53.48,0:45:57.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Noah lived in an extremely wicked world.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:57.15,0:46:00.61,Default,,0,0,0,,During his lifetime, rebel angels\Nleft their assignments in heaven,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:00.61,0:46:03.53,Default,,0,0,0,,materialized, married human women,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:03.53,0:46:07.37,Default,,0,0,0,,and fathered hybrid offspring\Nwho became violent giants.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:07.37,0:46:12.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, how did all of that wickedness\Nand violence affect Jehovah?
Dialogue: 0,0:46:12.92,0:46:15.80,Default,,0,0,0,,According to Genesis 6:6,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:15.79,0:46:18.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“his heart was saddened,”
Dialogue: 0,0:46:18.59,0:46:21.22,Default,,0,0,0,,which is a remarkable thing to contemplate,\Nisn’t it?
Dialogue: 0,0:46:21.22,0:46:23.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah’s feelings are affected
Dialogue: 0,0:46:23.38,0:46:27.76,Default,,0,0,0,,by our decisions because he cares for us.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:27.76,0:46:31.31,Default,,0,0,0,,That ancient world became so wicked
Dialogue: 0,0:46:31.31,0:46:34.52,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jehovah decided it must be destroyed.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:34.52,0:46:37.98,Default,,0,0,0,,And yet, right in the midst\Nof all this depravity,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:37.98,0:46:40.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Noah showed a different spirit.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:40.86,0:46:45.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice what it says at Genesis 6:8, 9:
Dialogue: 0,0:46:47.16,0:46:52.17,Default,,0,0,0,,“But Noah found favor in the eyes of Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:52.16,0:46:55.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“This is the history of Noah.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:55.75,0:46:59.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Noah was a righteous man.”
Dialogue: 0,0:46:59.59,0:47:00.80,Default,,0,0,0,,There it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:00.80,0:47:05.18,Default,,0,0,0,,And why was he described as righteous?
Dialogue: 0,0:47:05.18,0:47:08.77,Default,,0,0,0,,“He proved himself faultless
Dialogue: 0,0:47:08.76,0:47:11.01,Default,,0,0,0,,among his contemporaries.”
Dialogue: 0,0:47:11.02,0:47:13.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, Noah was not like the rebel angels
Dialogue: 0,0:47:13.48,0:47:16.78,Default,,0,0,0,,or their offspring\Nor like degraded human society.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:16.77,0:47:20.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“Noah walked with the true God.”
Dialogue: 0,0:47:21.48,0:47:25.28,Default,,0,0,0,,And thus the second time\Nwe find the word “righteous”
Dialogue: 0,0:47:25.28,0:47:29.41,Default,,0,0,0,,is at Genesis 7:1:
Dialogue: 0,0:47:29.41,0:47:32.12,Default,,0,0,0,,“After that, Jehovah said to Noah:
Dialogue: 0,0:47:32.12,0:47:35.04,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Go into the ark,\Nyou and all your household,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:35.04,0:47:37.79,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘because you are the one
Dialogue: 0,0:47:37.79,0:47:40.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I have found to be righteous
Dialogue: 0,0:47:40.88,0:47:45.30,Default,,0,0,0,,before me among this generation.’”
Dialogue: 0,0:47:45.30,0:47:47.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Because of Noah’s righteousness,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:47.97,0:47:50.93,Default,,0,0,0,,he and his family survived the Flood
Dialogue: 0,0:47:50.93,0:47:54.23,Default,,0,0,0,,to worship Jehovah on a cleansed earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:54.23,0:47:57.07,Default,,0,0,0,,And after the waters subsided
Dialogue: 0,0:47:57.06,0:48:00.15,Default,,0,0,0,,and the family emerged from the ark,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:00.15,0:48:02.99,Default,,0,0,0,,they witnessed a splendid sight,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:02.98,0:48:05.57,Default,,0,0,0,,one never before observed:
Dialogue: 0,0:48:05.57,0:48:08.82,Default,,0,0,0,,a serene, multicolored arch
Dialogue: 0,0:48:08.82,0:48:11.61,Default,,0,0,0,,in the sky\N—a rainbow—
Dialogue: 0,0:48:11.62,0:48:13.87,Default,,0,0,0,,a reassuring indication
Dialogue: 0,0:48:13.87,0:48:16.66,Default,,0,0,0,,of peace with God,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:16.66,0:48:20.87,Default,,0,0,0,,peace resulting from righteousness.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:20.88,0:48:23.47,Default,,0,0,0,,And where does the word “righteous”
Dialogue: 0,0:48:23.46,0:48:26.09,Default,,0,0,0,,appear next in the Bible?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:26.09,0:48:28.09,Default,,0,0,0,,In the account about Abraham
Dialogue: 0,0:48:28.09,0:48:31.01,Default,,0,0,0,,—notably in his famous conversation\Nwith Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:48:31.01,0:48:33.43,Default,,0,0,0,,found in Genesis chapter 18,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:33.43,0:48:35.68,Default,,0,0,0,,where Jehovah promised Abraham\Nthat if he found
Dialogue: 0,0:48:35.68,0:48:38.52,Default,,0,0,0,,as few as ten righteous people\Nin the city of Sodom,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:38.52,0:48:40.65,Default,,0,0,0,,he would not destroy that city.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:41.52,0:48:44.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what was it that distinguished Abraham
Dialogue: 0,0:48:44.57,0:48:48.24,Default,,0,0,0,,as righteous in that moral climate?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:48.24,0:48:51.66,Default,,0,0,0,,As you read Genesis chapters 12 through 22,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:51.66,0:48:54.08,Default,,0,0,0,,you get the sense that Abraham
Dialogue: 0,0:48:54.08,0:48:56.79,Default,,0,0,0,,was a man of great faith, unwavering faith.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:56.79,0:48:59.96,Default,,0,0,0,,He was ready to do whatever\NJehovah asked of him.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:59.96,0:49:03.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, citing Genesis 15:6
Dialogue: 0,0:49:03.54,0:49:07.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and other texts, James 2:23 says
Dialogue: 0,0:49:07.63,0:49:11.88,Default,,0,0,0,,that “‘Abraham put faith in Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:49:11.89,0:49:14.39,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and it was counted to him
Dialogue: 0,0:49:14.39,0:49:17.10,Default,,0,0,0,,“as righteousness,’
Dialogue: 0,0:49:17.10,0:49:22.06,Default,,0,0,0,,“and he came to be called Jehovah’s friend
Dialogue: 0,0:49:22.06,0:49:24.90,Default,,0,0,0,,“[Jehovah’s friend,
Dialogue: 0,0:49:24.90,0:49:28.74,Default,,0,0,0,,“peace with God resulting
Dialogue: 0,0:49:28.74,0:49:30.78,Default,,0,0,0,,from righteousness].”
Dialogue: 0,0:49:30.78,0:49:33.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what about God’s people today?
Dialogue: 0,0:49:33.83,0:49:37.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Turn with me, please, to Isaiah chapter 60
Dialogue: 0,0:49:37.66,0:49:41.29,Default,,0,0,0,,—Isaiah chapter 60.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:41.29,0:49:44.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah refers to Noah
Dialogue: 0,0:49:44.71,0:49:47.46,Default,,0,0,0,,and Abraham as “righteous.”
Dialogue: 0,0:49:47.46,0:49:50.96,Default,,0,0,0,,But what would he say about you and me?
Dialogue: 0,0:49:50.97,0:49:53.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, notice what it says\Ntoward the end of this chapter.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:53.85,0:49:56.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Isaiah chapter 60,
Dialogue: 0,0:49:56.47,0:50:00.64,Default,,0,0,0,,verses 21, 22:
Dialogue: 0,0:50:02.52,0:50:05.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“And all your people
Dialogue: 0,0:50:05.36,0:50:08.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“will be righteous;
Dialogue: 0,0:50:08.32,0:50:12.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“they will possess the land forever.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:12.20,0:50:14.66,Default,,0,0,0,,“They are the sprout that I planted,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:14.66,0:50:17.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“the work of my hands,\Nfor me to be beautified.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:17.95,0:50:22.33,Default,,0,0,0,,“The little one will become a thousand\Nand the small one a mighty nation.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:22.33,0:50:24.58,Default,,0,0,0,,“I myself, Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:24.58,0:50:27.46,Default,,0,0,0,,will speed it up in its own time.”
Dialogue: 0,0:50:28.55,0:50:31.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, prospective members of the great crowd
Dialogue: 0,0:50:31.88,0:50:36.89,Default,,0,0,0,,have been declared righteous\Nas friends of God as Abraham was.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:36.89,0:50:39.68,Default,,0,0,0,,In Jehovah’s eyes, they are, as it says
Dialogue: 0,0:50:39.68,0:50:44.27,Default,,0,0,0,,in Revelation 7:9, “dressed in white robes.”
Dialogue: 0,0:50:44.27,0:50:48.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Today, they’re serving\Nalongside God’s spirit-anointed ones
Dialogue: 0,0:50:48.44,0:50:50.73,Default,,0,0,0,,who are declared righteous for life.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:50.74,0:50:54.12,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jehovah, [our] Repurchaser,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:54.11,0:50:57.70,Default,,0,0,0,,the Holy One of Israel,” has bought us back
Dialogue: 0,0:50:57.70,0:51:00.33,Default,,0,0,0,,from bondage to sin and death
Dialogue: 0,0:51:00.33,0:51:04.17,Default,,0,0,0,,through the ransom sacrifice of Jesus Christ.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:04.17,0:51:06.30,Default,,0,0,0,,And thus with faith
Dialogue: 0,0:51:06.29,0:51:09.29,Default,,0,0,0,,in the ransom sacrifice of Jesus Christ,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:09.30,0:51:14.26,Default,,0,0,0,,imperfect people are considered righteous\Nin the sight of God.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:14.26,0:51:18.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, in calling us righteous,\NJehovah God by means of Jesus
Dialogue: 0,0:51:18.22,0:51:20.81,Default,,0,0,0,,has done something for us\Nthat we could not do
Dialogue: 0,0:51:20.81,0:51:22.85,Default,,0,0,0,,for ourselves in our imperfect condition.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:22.85,0:51:26.23,Default,,0,0,0,,But does that mean that we can do no wrong?
Dialogue: 0,0:51:27.31,0:51:30.52,Default,,0,0,0,,No, it does not mean that.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:31.57,0:51:33.91,Default,,0,0,0,,In order to maintain our peace,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:33.90,0:51:38.61,Default,,0,0,0,,we must cooperate with Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:38.62,0:51:41.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Turn with me, please, to Romans chapter 1.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:42.91,0:51:45.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, like Noah and Abraham,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:45.96,0:51:47.96,Default,,0,0,0,,we live in a wicked and violent world
Dialogue: 0,0:51:47.96,0:51:50.96,Default,,0,0,0,,where we are exposed\Nto a spirit of disobedience.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:50.96,0:51:53.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Satan wants us to become part of this world
Dialogue: 0,0:51:53.80,0:51:58.35,Default,,0,0,0,,by adopting its unrighteous standards.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:58.34,0:52:01.89,Default,,0,0,0,,In the world, sexual immorality\Nis practiced without shame.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:01.89,0:52:04.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Homosexuals flaunt their conduct.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:04.56,0:52:06.56,Default,,0,0,0,,But Jehovah tells us
Dialogue: 0,0:52:06.56,0:52:10.44,Default,,0,0,0,,that homosexual acts are unrighteous.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:10.44,0:52:14.61,Default,,0,0,0,,God specifically warned the Israelites
Dialogue: 0,0:52:14.61,0:52:17.78,Default,,0,0,0,,against this and other forms of immorality.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:17.78,0:52:21.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Leviticus 18:22 says
Dialogue: 0,0:52:21.20,0:52:25.41,Default,,0,0,0,,that homosexual acts are “detestable.”
Dialogue: 0,0:52:26.62,0:52:29.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Does Jehovah still find it so offensive?
Dialogue: 0,0:52:29.63,0:52:33.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, notice what he inspired\Nfor both Jews and non-Jews
Dialogue: 0,0:52:33.59,0:52:35.59,Default,,0,0,0,,in the Christian Greek Scriptures here
Dialogue: 0,0:52:35.59,0:52:39.97,Default,,0,0,0,,at Romans 1:26, 27:
Dialogue: 0,0:52:41.39,0:52:44.52,Default,,0,0,0,,“That is why God gave them over
Dialogue: 0,0:52:44.52,0:52:48.27,Default,,0,0,0,,“to disgraceful sexual passion,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:48.27,0:52:51.23,Default,,0,0,0,,“for their females changed the natural use
Dialogue: 0,0:52:51.23,0:52:53.82,Default,,0,0,0,,“of themselves into one contrary to nature;
Dialogue: 0,0:52:53.82,0:52:57.91,Default,,0,0,0,,“likewise also the males left\Nthe natural use of the female
Dialogue: 0,0:52:57.90,0:53:01.65,Default,,0,0,0,,“and became violently inflamed\Nin their lust toward one another,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:01.66,0:53:05.16,Default,,0,0,0,,“males with males, working what is obscene
Dialogue: 0,0:53:05.16,0:53:08.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“and receiving\Nin themselves the full penalty,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:08.21,0:53:11.38,Default,,0,0,0,,which was due for their error.”
Dialogue: 0,0:53:11.38,0:53:15.13,Default,,0,0,0,,So Jehovah has not changed.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:15.13,0:53:18.09,Default,,0,0,0,,According to the Creator, homosexual acts
Dialogue: 0,0:53:18.09,0:53:21.09,Default,,0,0,0,,constitute disgraceful,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:21.09,0:53:23.38,Default,,0,0,0,,obscene error.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:24.60,0:53:26.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Some would disagree.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:26.60,0:53:28.81,Default,,0,0,0,,As verse 28 points out,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:28.81,0:53:33.32,Default,,0,0,0,,such ones do not consider it\Nworthwhile “to acknowledge God.”
Dialogue: 0,0:53:33.31,0:53:35.85,Default,,0,0,0,,But with what result?
Dialogue: 0,0:53:35.86,0:53:40.03,Default,,0,0,0,,As it says there,\N“a disapproved mental state”
Dialogue: 0,0:53:40.03,0:53:42.66,Default,,0,0,0,,—just the opposite of peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:42.66,0:53:47.33,Default,,0,0,0,,And merely approving\Nof unrighteous conduct displeases Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:47.33,0:53:51.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice how this is indicated in verse 32:
Dialogue: 0,0:53:51.04,0:53:55.54,Default,,0,0,0,,“Although these know full well\Nthe righteous decree of God
Dialogue: 0,0:53:55.54,0:53:59.13,Default,,0,0,0,,“—that those practicing such things\Nare deserving of death—
Dialogue: 0,0:53:59.13,0:54:01.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“they not only keep on doing them
Dialogue: 0,0:54:01.51,0:54:06.06,Default,,0,0,0,,but also approve of those practicing them.”
Dialogue: 0,0:54:07.18,0:54:10.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, we do not hate individuals
Dialogue: 0,0:54:10.81,0:54:13.52,Default,,0,0,0,,who practice unrighteousness,\Nnor do we judge them.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:13.52,0:54:15.81,Default,,0,0,0,,On the contrary,\Nwe share the good news with them.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:15.82,0:54:19.16,Default,,0,0,0,,We remember that we were all born\Nwith the same infirmities
Dialogue: 0,0:54:19.15,0:54:21.57,Default,,0,0,0,,and have the same sinful tendencies.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:21.57,0:54:26.12,Default,,0,0,0,,But we also have\Nthe same inherent spiritual need.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:26.12,0:54:29.25,Default,,0,0,0,,And thus, we recognize that others\Ncan have the same peace,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:29.25,0:54:32.88,Default,,0,0,0,,the same privileges,\Nand the same prospects we enjoy
Dialogue: 0,0:54:32.87,0:54:37.00,Default,,0,0,0,,if they pay attention to Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:37.00,0:54:41.84,Default,,0,0,0,,First Timothy 2:3, 4 says\Nthat God’s “will is that all sorts of people
Dialogue: 0,0:54:41.84,0:54:44.76,Default,,0,0,0,,should be saved\Nand come to an accurate knowledge of truth.”
Dialogue: 0,0:54:44.76,0:54:47.81,Default,,0,0,0,,And people practicing\Nall manner of unrighteousness
Dialogue: 0,0:54:47.81,0:54:49.85,Default,,0,0,0,,have accepted the truth.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:49.85,0:54:53.94,Default,,0,0,0,,“That is what some of you were,”\N1 Corinthians 6:11 says.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:53.94,0:54:57.53,Default,,0,0,0,,So we communicate impartially\Nwith all our neighbors.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:57.52,0:55:00.19,Default,,0,0,0,,But we hate unrighteous conduct,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:00.19,0:55:04.15,Default,,0,0,0,,and we refuse to compromise Bible principles.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:04.99,0:55:06.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, sometimes moral issues
Dialogue: 0,0:55:06.99,0:55:09.99,Default,,0,0,0,,become the center\Nof heated political debates.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:09.99,0:55:13.12,Default,,0,0,0,,We avoid getting drawn\Ninto such controversies.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:13.12,0:55:18.08,Default,,0,0,0,,But now, in practical terms,\Nwhat might that look like?
Dialogue: 0,0:55:18.09,0:55:21.39,Default,,0,0,0,,In the following video, notice how adults
Dialogue: 0,0:55:21.38,0:55:26.18,Default,,0,0,0,,can respond effectively when questioned\Non highly controversial issues.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:37.98,0:55:39.61,Default,,0,0,0,,There you are.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:40.32,0:55:42.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Did you both get the email survey I sent?
Dialogue: 0,0:55:42.86,0:55:44.07,Default,,0,0,0,,And you’re both coming, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:55:44.07,0:55:46.45,Default,,0,0,0,,I must have missed it.\NI was on calls all morning.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:46.45,0:55:47.66,Default,,0,0,0,,What’s this about?
Dialogue: 0,0:55:47.66,0:55:49.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, the whole office is leaving early.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:49.83,0:55:52.75,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re going downtown\Nto support the march
Dialogue: 0,0:55:52.75,0:55:54.75,Default,,0,0,0,,for gay rights.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:55.50,0:55:57.50,Default,,0,0,0,,She won’t go.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:57.50,0:55:58.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Why?
Dialogue: 0,0:55:58.75,0:56:00.42,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s against her religion.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:00.42,0:56:02.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Some of her people came by my house,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:02.42,0:56:05.30,Default,,0,0,0,,and when I asked, they said your church
Dialogue: 0,0:56:05.30,0:56:07.30,Default,,0,0,0,,won’t support gay marriage.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:08.18,0:56:09.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Irene?
Dialogue: 0,0:56:12.72,0:56:13.93,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s true.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:13.93,0:56:17.89,Default,,0,0,0,,As Jehovah’s Witnesses,\Nwe hold to the Bible’s standard on marriage,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:17.90,0:56:21.45,Default,,0,0,0,,which is only between a man and woman.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:21.44,0:56:23.90,Default,,0,0,0,,And we remain politically neutral.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:23.90,0:56:26.57,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s such ignorant thinking.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:28.70,0:56:31.50,Default,,0,0,0,,I understand it’s a sensitive subject.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:31.49,0:56:35.08,Default,,0,0,0,,I have a daughter who deserves her rights!
Dialogue: 0,0:56:35.08,0:56:39.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Trust me, Amber,\Nas one of Jehovah’s Witnesses,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:39.63,0:56:43.05,Default,,0,0,0,,we believe everyone has a right\Nto choose how they live.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:43.05,0:56:46.26,Default,,0,0,0,,And I would never force my beliefs on anyone.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:46.26,0:56:48.43,Default,,0,0,0,,But you won’t go.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:48.43,0:56:50.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Just as I would never force\Nmy beliefs on you,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:50.51,0:56:53.26,Default,,0,0,0,,all I ask is the same respect.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:54.31,0:56:56.31,Default,,0,0,0,,And, no, I won’t be going.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:56.31,0:56:58.31,Default,,0,0,0,,I have to go back to work.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:03.32,0:57:05.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Look, obviously, Irene,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:05.99,0:57:08.20,Default,,0,0,0,,I don’t agree with your perspective.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:08.99,0:57:12.16,Default,,0,0,0,,But I do appreciate\Nthat you not push it on anyone else.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:12.16,0:57:13.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:25.50,0:57:29.30,Default,,0,0,0,,In contrast with the majority of mankind\Nwho are divided,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:29.30,0:57:31.97,Default,,0,0,0,,true Christians are united.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:31.97,0:57:35.39,Default,,0,0,0,,We loyally support Jehovah’s right to rule.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:35.39,0:57:37.02,Default,,0,0,0,,We don’t set the standards,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:37.02,0:57:39.65,Default,,0,0,0,,and we’re not trying\Nto solve the world’s problems on our own.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:39.64,0:57:42.10,Default,,0,0,0,,We fully support God’s Kingdom.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:42.10,0:57:44.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, as we observed in the video,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:44.11,0:57:47.78,Default,,0,0,0,,moral and political issues\Nmight be brought up in the workplace.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:47.78,0:57:51.95,Default,,0,0,0,,But more often our young ones,\Neven very young ones,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:51.95,0:57:54.54,Default,,0,0,0,,are confronted with these same topics.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:54.53,0:57:56.53,Default,,0,0,0,,How will they respond?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:56.54,0:57:59.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Are your young ones ready?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:59.04,0:58:01.04,Default,,0,0,0,,As you watch the next video,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:01.04,0:58:05.46,Default,,0,0,0,,notice how Olivia defends\NJehovah’s righteous standards.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:07.42,0:58:09.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Great discussion today, everyone.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:09.47,0:58:11.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember, midterms are this Friday.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:11.59,0:58:13.43,Default,,0,0,0,,No excuses!
Dialogue: 0,0:58:13.43,0:58:15.43,Default,,0,0,0,,That includes you, Jordan.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:16.18,0:58:19.85,Default,,0,0,0,,You were noticeably silent\Nduring our discussion today, Olivia.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:20.73,0:58:21.94,Default,,0,0,0,,I was?
Dialogue: 0,0:58:21.94,0:58:24.53,Default,,0,0,0,,I guess I just didn’t have much to say.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:25.23,0:58:27.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Aren’t you concerned about gay rights?
Dialogue: 0,0:58:27.98,0:58:29.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Um,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:29.65,0:58:32.32,Default,,0,0,0,,well, it seems like a political issue,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:32.32,0:58:36.24,Default,,0,0,0,,and I stay neutral\Nwhen it comes to political stuff.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:36.24,0:58:38.49,Default,,0,0,0,,But it’s not a political issue.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:38.49,0:58:40.49,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a human rights issue.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:40.50,0:58:42.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Mr. Dallas,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:42.29,0:58:43.79,Default,,0,0,0,,she’s like crazy religious.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:43.79,0:58:44.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey!
Dialogue: 0,0:58:44.38,0:58:45.59,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s nothing wrong with that.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:45.58,0:58:46.79,Default,,0,0,0,,No, you don’t understand.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:46.79,0:58:49.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah’s Witnesses\Nhate everybody that isn’t straight.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:49.30,0:58:51.55,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s not true! \NWe don’t hate anyone.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:51.55,0:58:53.59,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve spoken with your people before.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:54.80,0:58:56.51,Default,,0,0,0,,They seem big on equality.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:56.51,0:58:57.72,Default,,0,0,0,,We are.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:57.72,0:58:59.60,Default,,0,0,0,,The Bible says that ‘God isn’t partial.’
Dialogue: 0,0:58:59.60,0:59:02.81,Default,,0,0,0,,So we believe that everyone\Nshould be treated fairly.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:04.02,0:59:05.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Good.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:05.94,0:59:09.07,Default,,0,0,0,,So I assume you have\Ngay members in your church.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:10.65,0:59:12.74,Default,,0,0,0,,No, we don’t.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:15.53,0:59:18.32,Default,,0,0,0,,But I thought you just said\Neveryone should be treated equally?
Dialogue: 0,0:59:19.33,0:59:21.33,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m confused.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:21.33,0:59:22.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Hah, called it!
Dialogue: 0,0:59:22.75,0:59:25.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Jordan, don’t you have a class to get to?
Dialogue: 0,0:59:26.71,0:59:28.71,Default,,0,0,0,,As I was saying,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:29.71,0:59:32.71,Default,,0,0,0,,how is that not a little hypocritical,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:32.71,0:59:36.46,Default,,0,0,0,,saying that you love everyone\Nand then excluding certain people?
Dialogue: 0,0:59:44.23,0:59:46.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Honestly, Mr. Dallas,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:49.06,0:59:51.10,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve wondered the same thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:51.69,0:59:53.15,Default,,0,0,0,,OK.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:54.11,0:59:55.57,Default,,0,0,0,,And?
Dialogue: 0,0:59:55.57,0:59:58.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, I researched it in the Bible,\Nand I realized
Dialogue: 0,0:59:58.95,1:00:03.12,Default,,0,0,0,,that God accepts all people,\Nbut he doesn’t accept all conduct.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:05.46,1:00:07.50,Default,,0,0,0,,What does that mean?
Dialogue: 0,1:00:08.83,1:00:12.50,Default,,0,0,0,,It means that you can’t be abusing drugs
Dialogue: 0,1:00:12.50,1:00:14.84,Default,,0,0,0,,and you can’t be stealing
Dialogue: 0,1:00:14.84,1:00:18.68,Default,,0,0,0,,or be violent and still be a Witness.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:19.68,1:00:23.68,Default,,0,0,0,,There are just certain actions\Nthat God just doesn’t accept.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:26.81,1:00:30.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Including how someone expresses\Ntheir sexuality?
Dialogue: 0,1:00:31.86,1:00:33.28,Default,,0,0,0,,In some cases, yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:33.28,1:00:35.28,Default,,0,0,0,,We follow God’s standards
Dialogue: 0,1:00:35.28,1:00:37.87,Default,,0,0,0,,—not having sex without being married.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:38.91,1:00:39.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Well,
Dialogue: 0,1:00:41.58,1:00:44.58,Default,,0,0,0,,if that’s how you feel, that’s your right.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:44.58,1:00:48.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Personally, it seems a tad archaic to me 
Dialogue: 0,1:00:48.50,1:00:50.54,Default,,0,0,0,,but to each their own.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:57.72,1:00:58.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:58.72,1:00:59.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:59.72,1:01:02.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Does the Bible really say all that?
Dialogue: 0,1:01:02.76,1:01:05.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, it does.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:05.18,1:01:06.18,Default,,0,0,0,,OK,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:06.18,1:01:08.18,Default,,0,0,0,,maybe you can show me sometime.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:08.19,1:01:09.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, for sure.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:09.60,1:01:10.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Awesome.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:35.17,1:01:39.42,Default,,0,0,0,,So we can expect future installments\Nin this saga.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:39.42,1:01:41.84,Default,,0,0,0,,But did you notice how Olivia
Dialogue: 0,1:01:41.84,1:01:45.14,Default,,0,0,0,,was able to defend\NJehovah’s righteous standards?
Dialogue: 0,1:01:45.14,1:01:47.89,Default,,0,0,0,,She kept her peaceful spirit, didn’t she?
Dialogue: 0,1:01:47.89,1:01:50.73,Default,,0,0,0,,She acknowledged that she had\Nthe same question as the teacher,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:50.73,1:01:53.44,Default,,0,0,0,,but she had done further\Nresearch on the subject.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:53.44,1:01:57.32,Default,,0,0,0,,And did you appreciate how she\Nsubtly showed that Jehovah’s standards
Dialogue: 0,1:01:57.32,1:02:00.78,Default,,0,0,0,,benefit both the individual\Nand the community?
Dialogue: 0,1:02:00.78,1:02:04.70,Default,,0,0,0,,As examples, she highlighted\Nthe avoidance of drug abuse and theft,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:04.70,1:02:07.41,Default,,0,0,0,,values she knew her teacher would appreciate.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:08.66,1:02:11.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Parents, are your young ones
Dialogue: 0,1:02:11.12,1:02:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,able to explain why we do
Dialogue: 0,1:02:14.00,1:02:16.50,Default,,0,0,0,,or don’t do certain things?
Dialogue: 0,1:02:16.50,1:02:18.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you know how your children
Dialogue: 0,1:02:18.71,1:02:21.42,Default,,0,0,0,,really feel about Jehovah’s standards?
Dialogue: 0,1:02:21.43,1:02:25.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Are they obedient simply\Nto avoid making you mad?
Dialogue: 0,1:02:25.89,1:02:30.85,Default,,0,0,0,,If so, will that truly be enough?
Dialogue: 0,1:02:30.85,1:02:32.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Encourage your young ones
Dialogue: 0,1:02:32.85,1:02:36.90,Default,,0,0,0,,to prove to themselves\Nwhy Jehovah’s standards are wise.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:36.90,1:02:39.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Help them to see how they can explain
Dialogue: 0,1:02:39.44,1:02:41.98,Default,,0,0,0,,their choice to live by Jehovah’s standards.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:41.99,1:02:46.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Teach them how to resist pressure\Nto follow the world.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:48.87,1:02:51.62,Default,,0,0,0,,We are so thankful
Dialogue: 0,1:02:51.62,1:02:55.92,Default,,0,0,0,,that even during these\N“critical times hard to deal with”
Dialogue: 0,1:02:55.92,1:03:00.63,Default,,0,0,0,,we can enjoy the inner peace\Nthat Jehovah gives to the righteous.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:00.63,1:03:04.97,Default,,0,0,0,,But let’s remind ourselves of what Jehovah\Npromises to bring about
Dialogue: 0,1:03:04.97,1:03:08.85,Default,,0,0,0,,once Satan’s unrighteous system is removed.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:08.85,1:03:12.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Turn with me, please, to Psalm 37.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:13.94,1:03:16.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Here in these familiar verses,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:16.19,1:03:19.86,Default,,0,0,0,,we find a beautiful description\Nof what is to come.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:19.86,1:03:21.99,Default,,0,0,0,,And notice once again
Dialogue: 0,1:03:21.99,1:03:24.28,Default,,0,0,0,,how the Bible makes the correlation
Dialogue: 0,1:03:24.28,1:03:27.78,Default,,0,0,0,,between peace and righteousness
Dialogue: 0,1:03:27.78,1:03:30.78,Default,,0,0,0,,—Psalm 37:29.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:30.79,1:03:32.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you have it?
Dialogue: 0,1:03:32.79,1:03:35.17,Default,,0,0,0,,What does it say?
Dialogue: 0,1:03:35.17,1:03:38.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Who will possess the earth?
Dialogue: 0,1:03:38.46,1:03:40.09,Default,,0,0,0,,“The righteous.”
Dialogue: 0,1:03:40.09,1:03:43.30,Default,,0,0,0,,And for how long will they live on it?
Dialogue: 0,1:03:43.30,1:03:45.30,Default,,0,0,0,,“Forever.”
Dialogue: 0,1:03:45.30,1:03:50.14,Default,,0,0,0,,And then according to verse 11,\Nwhat will they find there?
Dialogue: 0,1:03:51.47,1:03:53.10,Default,,0,0,0,,“Peace.”
Dialogue: 0,1:03:53.10,1:03:56.98,Default,,0,0,0,,The result of true righteousness\Nwill be peace.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:56.98,1:03:59.07,Default,,0,0,0,,And how much peace will they find?
Dialogue: 0,1:03:59.06,1:04:02.06,Default,,0,0,0,,a little peace?\Njust personal or family peace?
Dialogue: 0,1:04:02.07,1:04:04.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember, the righteous\Nalready had peace with God,
Dialogue: 0,1:04:04.11,1:04:06.24,Default,,0,0,0,,even when wicked people still existed.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:06.24,1:04:10.37,Default,,0,0,0,,But what will Jehovah provide\Nto all those who continue loving him?
Dialogue: 0,1:04:11.54,1:04:14.75,Default,,0,0,0,,The abundance of peace.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:14.75,1:04:17.71,Default,,0,0,0,,And how will you feel about that?
Dialogue: 0,1:04:17.71,1:04:22.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Delighted or exquisitely delighted?
Dialogue: 0,1:04:22.38,1:04:24.38,Default,,0,0,0,,So stick with it, dear friends.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:24.38,1:04:27.38,Default,,0,0,0,,During this convention, be on the lookout\Nfor the connection
Dialogue: 0,1:04:27.38,1:04:29.84,Default,,0,0,0,,between peace and righteousness.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:29.85,1:04:32.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Continue on the course of righteousness.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:32.01,1:04:34.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Help others to find “the way of peace.”
Dialogue: 0,1:04:34.52,1:04:37.77,Default,,0,0,0,,In that way, we can enjoy peace\Nwith Jehovah now,
Dialogue: 0,1:04:37.77,1:04:40.19,Default,,0,0,0,,throughout the remainder of these last days,
Dialogue: 0,1:04:40.19,1:04:44.65,Default,,0,0,0,,and on into the future when Jesus\Nrules as King over a cleansed earth
Dialogue: 0,1:04:44.65,1:04:49.28,Default,,0,0,0,,in which “the righteous will flourish\Nand peace will abound.”
Dialogue: 0,1:04:51.16,1:04:54.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you, Brother Schafer,\Nfor helping us to understand
Dialogue: 0,1:04:54.66,1:04:57.37,Default,,0,0,0,,why upholding Jehovah’s righteousness
Dialogue: 0,1:04:57.37,1:05:00.37,Default,,0,0,0,,is essential for enjoying true peace.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:01.84,1:05:04.18,Default,,0,0,0,,We have been well-instructed
Dialogue: 0,1:05:04.17,1:05:07.80,Default,,0,0,0,,during this first session of our convention,\Nhaven’t we?
Dialogue: 0,1:05:07.80,1:05:10.18,Default,,0,0,0,,We look forward to our next session
Dialogue: 0,1:05:10.18,1:05:12.89,Default,,0,0,0,,in which we will consider in greater detail
Dialogue: 0,1:05:12.89,1:05:17.02,Default,,0,0,0,,promises of peace found in God’s Word.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:17.02,1:05:21.15,Default,,0,0,0,,We will also see how Bible principles\Ncan help families
Dialogue: 0,1:05:21.15,1:05:23.53,Default,,0,0,0,,to enjoy greater peace now
Dialogue: 0,1:05:23.52,1:05:27.57,Default,,0,0,0,,and how we can avoid pursuing\Nimitation peace.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:29.95,1:05:32.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s conclude this session
Dialogue: 0,1:05:32.57,1:05:36.28,Default,,0,0,0,,by singing song number 97, entitled
Dialogue: 0,1:05:36.29,1:05:39.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“Life Depends on God’s Word.”
Dialogue: 0,1:05:39.75,1:05:41.75,Default,,0,0,0,,After singing the song,
Dialogue: 0,1:05:41.75,1:05:45.00,Default,,0,0,0,,you may have your local concluding prayer.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:45.00,1:05:48.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Again, that’s song number 97.
